INSERT INTO PatientInsights VALUES('Is Cryotherapy an alternative for me', 'August 2018', 'Patient is inquiring if Cryotherapy is an appropriate alternative to chemotherapy or hormone therapy', '[Cryotherapy vs. Chemotherapy]; [Cyrotherapy vs. Hormone Therapy]', 'stage II', 'Comparing Therapies', '[Chemotherapy vs. Cryotherapy]', 'Cryoablation is currently experimental (in some treatment centers and clinical trials). There may be some success with cryoablation and immunotheraph', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/866601', '', ''),
('Is Cryotherapy an alternative for me', 'August 15, 2018', '', '', 'Stage II BC', 'Comparing Therapies', '[Chemotherapy vs. Cryotherapy]', 'Another alternative is cryoablation with immunotherapy, the patient clains that it is too early to determine if it was successful but has spoken to a previous patient who has had no since of BC for 5+ years after this treatment. There are a lot of studies with positive results for this alternative treatment.', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/866601', '', ''),
('5cm tumor - lumpectomy vs. Mastectomy', '', '', '', 'Stage IIA grade 3 BC', 'Comparing Therapies', '', 'Lumpectomy is more ideal for smaller tumors while mastectomy is ideal for tumors near the chest wall or larger than 5 cm. Lumpectomy can be preferred for cosmetic reasons(there will be more tissue left for reconstruction) but comes at a higher risk of recurrence and the need for additional radiation.  ', '?', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/863920', '', ''),
('5cm tumor - lumpectomy vs. Mastectomy', '', '', '', 'Stage IIA Grade 3 Breast cancer', 'Comparing Therapies', '', 'Diagnosed with 2 5cm tumors within very close proximity, currently undergoing hormonal therapy (Aromansin & Zoladex). Doctor is recommending a masectomy but patient is curious about getting a lumpectomy. The cause that lead to the diagnosis is because the tumors are very close to eachother, which will require a masectomy, but patient is wanting to avoid the masectomy. According to the discussion boards the masectomy is the best route to go.', 'Jaspreet Deol', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/863920', '', ''),
('5cm tumor - lumpectomy vs. Mastectomy', 'March 2018', '', 'Stage IIA, Two tumors on right each 2cm, Grade 3, 0/7 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER-', 'Stage 2, recomended of mastectomy, inqury of lumpectomy as an alternative', 'Comparing Therapies', '', 'The location of the tumor might br making lumpectomy a difficult option. For instance, tumors closer to the chest wall makes lumpectomy difficult.', 'Ricky Fukuyama', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/863920', '', ''),
('5cm tumor - lumpectomy vs. Mastectomy', '', 'I have two tumors close together in the 3 and 4 o\'clock position. Together they cover a 5cm (2cm each) area. I have DD breasts but my surgeon says I need a mastectomy. Is this the right treatment for me?', '', 'Stage II BC', 'Comparing Therapies', '', 'Choice between lumpectomy and mastectomy depends on personal preferences and both options are reasonable. Key factors include size of tumor (lumpectomy better for smaller tumors), reconstruction potential (will there be enough tissue left over after lumpectomy for reconstruction), proximity to chest wall (mastectomy better if tumor close to chest wall) and willingness to put up with radiation (lumpectomy requires radiation). An awesome list of additional considerations in \'Interesting Followup\' tab', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/863920', '', ''),
('84 yr old Mom, Stage 2, Lymph node, CHEMO normal?', '', '', '', 'Stage 2 breast cancer ', 'Comparing Therapies', '', 'Patient does not know if she should have been offered chemotherapy as an option for treatment instead of only Lumpectomy, Radiation, and hormone therapy. Patient with HER2-  and lymph nodes involved', 'Christina Ton ', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/849359', '', ''),
('84 yr old Mom, Stage 2, Lymph node, CHEMO normal?', '', '', '', 'Stage 2 BC, Invasive Ductal Carcinoma', 'Comparing Therapies', '', 'Had a 1.8 cm tumor on her back breast, surgeon was doing biopsy for mysectomy without patient permission, has chosen a different surgeon since. Doctors had said the tumor could be removed via lumpectomy but cells that are left over will be killed off with radiation, but non-surgery options should be avoided in someone the patients age. Oncologist had said that tumor was 100% Estrogen, 100% Progesterone, and HER2 Negative with lymph nodes involved. Patient\'s child is looking for answers. Her oncologist is not convinced her other growth found on the left side of her thyroid is a tumor.', 'Jaspreet Deol', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/849359', '', ''),
('84 yr old Mom, Stage 2, Lymph node, CHEMO normal?', 'September \'16', '', '', 'Stage 2 BC, HER2-', 'Comparing Therapies', '', 'Chemotherapy is not adviced for people over 70 years of age as it can have side effects. Surgery should be followed by honmonal therapy.', 'Preetham Ramesh', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/849359', '', ''),
('Decisions re: ovaries/estrogen', 'January 2019', '', '', 'Stage 2 IDC', 'Comparing Therapies', '', '', 'Preetham Ramesh', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/821080', '', ''),
('Finished chemo,considering Oophorectomy/Hysterectomy-confused!', 'July 9th 2015', 'Patient needs help discering between ooprectomy or hysterectomy or both', 'The original poster had double masecotomy and finished chemotherapy, and is gene negative. Because she is premenopausal, she discussed starting Tamoxifen with her MO, and is considering having her ovaries and uterus removed, which she wants advice on.', 'Stage II Breast Cancer', 'Comparing Therapies', '', 'Losing Estrogen can have different effects, so it\'s reccomended to take it slow and start with Tamoxifen instead of getting the surgery righ away. Previewing ovarian suppression with lupron and laparoscopic oopherectomy instead of hysterectomy is also an option. Finally, the OP said that she would start Tamoxifen, then monthly zoladex once her period starts, then then think about oopherectomy because its easing into the surgery better.', 'Devansh Dwivedy', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/833273', '', ''),
('Finished chemo,considering Oophorectomy/Hysterectomy-confused!', 'July 10th, 2015', '', 'Stage IIA ER+/PR+, HER2- IDC', 'Stage 1 ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'Comparing Therapies', '', 'The body can react to the surgeries in different ways, the sudden absence of estrogen in your system can cause physical changes that can be positive or negative. Many say that the hysterectomy is not necessary more so a laporascopic oopherectomy. Before going through with the surgery recommended to take ovary suppression drugs such as Lupron or Zoladex to see how the body will react without the estrogen. If negative effects than try transitioning to the surgery with the Tamoxifen and suppression drugs.', 'Sarah Taga', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/833273', '', ''),
('Finished chemo,considering Oophorectomy/Hysterectomy-confused!', 'July 10th, 2015', '', 'Stage IIA ER+/PR+, HER2- IDC', 'Stage 1 ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'Comparing Therapies', '', 'A hysterectomy is invasive and isnt very necessary even when being extremely thorough. More so an oopherectomy which is a factor in hormone dispersal and menopause. It would be a better idea to transition into the surgery before making a decision, staying on the Tamoxifen and taking ovary suppression drugs to see how the body will respond to the surgery.', 'Sarah Taga ', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/833273', '', ''),
('Looking for Advice', '', '', '', 'Stage II breast cancer ', 'Comparing Therapies', '', 'Oncotype DX test isn\'t for node-positive cancer. The patient may ask their doctor about the EndoPredict test to predict the risk of distance recurrence of early-stage, hormone-receptor-positive, HER2-negative breast cancer that is node-negative/has up to 3 positive lymph nodes. There is an official oncotype test for node positive cancer that\'s called Oncotype DX breast Recurrence Score Micromets & Node Positive', 'Kelvin Du', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/870003', '', 'Appropriate use of Oncotype DX'),
('Just diagnosed with stage2B', 'Jan 2018', 'Pt has to decide between AC or Carboplatin and wants to know success stories of either.', '', 'Stage II B', 'Comparing Therapies; AC/Taxol vs. Carboplatin/Taxol', '', 'Although there weren\'t any insights for the effect of carboplatin on the body, there were many for AC therapy. The general consensus being that AC had some side effects that caused tiredness and soreness in the body, but at a manageable level.', 'Geon Kim', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/861984', '', ''),
('Chemo confusion', 'March 2019', '', '', 'Stage II Grade 2 BC', 'Comparing Therapies; Chemotheraphy; TC vs A-CT', '', 'Patient had a mastectomy for a 1.2cm IDC. The patient is deciding between TC chemotherapy and A-CT. A-CT is normally used for patients who have a more invasive form of breast cancer (grade 2 or higher and high oncotype score). Other patients with grade 3 cells reported having A-CT chemotherapy. Patients with lower oncotype scores reported the TC chemotherapy treatment.', 'Dhriti Bolangadi', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/870206', '', ''),
('Chemo confusion', 'March 2019', '', '', 'Stage II', 'Comparing Therapies; Chemotheraphy; TC vs A-CT', '', 'Patient had a unilateral mastectomy for a 1.2 cm IDC and found two positive lymph nodes. Patient has er+, her2-, low ki-67 (<10) and oncotype score 8. One oncologist recommends TC and another suggests A-CT. Patients notes that others with similar situations do often use TC.', 'Lin Weingarten', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/870206', '', ''),
('Chemo confusion', '', 'There is a discrepancy between two doctors\' recommendations about chemotherapy (TC vs ACT). Any advice on which might be better.  ', '', '', 'Comparing Therapies; Chemotheraphy; TC vs A-CT', '', '', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/870206', '', ''),
('Is Cryotherapy an alternative for me', '', '', '', 'stage II, RO+ (risk-organ), RP+ (radiation pneumatosis), HER2- (oncogenge), KI67 20% (replication involved protein expression) Breast cancer reoccurance. ', 'Comparing Therapies; Chemotherapy vs. Cryotherapy', '[Chemotherapy vs. Cryotherapy]', 'Is chryotherapy/cryoablation an alternative to chemo/hormone therapy for reoccurance. Neuropathy syptoms during Taxol chemotherapy can be reduced with wearing cryotheriputic socks (~90 min)', 'Harrison Klinski', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/866601', 'Does RP+ mean testing positive for radiation pneumatosis? ', ''),
('Is Cryotherapy an alternative for me', 'August 2018', '', 'Stage II, RO+, RP+, HER2-, KI67 20%', 'Recurring stage II breast cancer, weighing choices of alternate treatments', 'Comparing Therapies; Chemotherapy vs. Cryotherapy', '[Chemotherapy vs. Cryotherapy]', 'Cryotherapy is a prospective alternative to breast cancer surgery that is still tested whether it is a good substitute. Furthermore, cryotherapy paired with immunotherapy could elicit better outcomes.\nSide effects of Taxol chemotherapy, peripheral neuropathy, could be mitigated by wearing frozen glove and socks for 90 min. But so far this has been exclusively tested on Taxol chemo, and whether the benefits will carry on to various cancer drugs is unknown.\n', 'Ricky Fukuyama', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/866601', '', ''),
('Is Cryotherapy an alternative for me', 'August 2018', '', 'She wrote: stage II, RO+, RP+, HER2-,KI67 20%', 'Stage II BC', 'Comparing Therapies; Chemotherapy vs. Cryotherapy', '[Chemotherapy vs. Cryotherapy]', '', 'Kendall Vanderwouw', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/866601', '', ''),
('chemotherapy or not', '', '', '', 'Stage IIA, Grade 1', 'Comparing Therapies; Chemotherapy; Tamoxifene vs. Decapeptyl ', '', 'Chemotheraphy is a personal choice. There are various drugs that can combat nausea and sickness during chemotherphy but it is up to the patient to make a decision that they will not regret later on. Most physicians want to throw everything at the cancer so usually recommend chemotheraphy.', 'Hamza Hussain', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/814378', '', ''),
('chemotherapy or not', 'November 12, 2013', '', '', 'Stage IIA Grade 1 IDC', 'Comparing Therapies; Chemotherapy; Tamoxifene vs. Decapeptyl ', '', 'With 3 node positives chemotherapy could be recommended but if oncotype is low maybe not. Also chemotherapy shouldnt be needed if 2mm or less. Most important thing is choosing which option is bedt for you personally.', 'Sarah Taga', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/814378', '', ''),
('Ibrance for stage 2, how are you tolerating.', 'Nov. 25th/2017', '', 'Grade 1. 2 of 2 nodes positive, oncotopye 19, and low Mammoprint', 'Stage 2b BC', 'Comparing Therapies; Ibrance', '', '', 'Zihan Zheng', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/860393', '', ''),
('Ibrance for stage 2, how are you tolerating.', 'Nov 25, 2017', '', 'Patient skipped chemo but had 28 rads, on letrozole', 'Stage IIB, IDC, Right, 2cm, Grade I, 2/2 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'Comparing Therapies; Ibrance', '', 'Patient considering Ibrance, but responder suggested doing Xeloda instead. \"Having this kind of preventative treatment gives me peace of mind.\"\"\"', 'Valerie Chen', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/860393', '', ''),
('Ibrance for stage 2, how are you tolerating.', 'Nov 25, 2017', 'Patient is inquiring regarding an Ibrance study and how other patients have handled it', 'Grade 1. 2 of 2 nodes positive, ER+/PR+, HER2-. oncotopye 19, and low Mammoprint. IDC, Right, 2 cm. ', 'Stage 2b BC', 'Comparing Therapies; Ibrance', '', 'Most patients are also considering this study but there is no clear side effects list. Other patients have decided to go with Xeloda which is a preventive treatment and allows for peace of mind. ', 'Hamza Hussain', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/860393', '', ''),
('84 yr old Mom, Stage 2, Lymph node, CHEMO normal?', 'September 2016', 'Should my elderly mom (with a certain history/profile) not be given chemo?', '', 'Stage II, HR+, HER2-, elderly (80+)', 'Comparing Therapies; Right treatment?', '', 'In the elderly, chemo should be avoided if possible. For HR+, patients could go with just anti-hormonals after surgery. ', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/849359', '', 'Data around utility of chemo, radiation in elderly with HR+? What do the guidelines say?'),
('Confused as why everyone seems to have surgery first', 'June 2014', '', '', 'Stage 2B ER/PR- HER2+', 'Comparing Therapies; Surgery vs. Chemotherapy', '', 'Surgery is the best option for oncotype testing, but due to the status of the patient being HER2+ and Stage 2, neoadjuntive chemotherapy is the best option for aggressive cancers like this. Getting chemotherapy also can prevent future use of hormonal therapies. The order of chemo and surgery also depends on the type o surgery, might do chemo first to shrink the tumor. ', 'Deepthi Mohanraj', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/821821', '', ''),
('Confused as why everyone seems to have surgery first', 'June 2014', '', '', 'Stage IIB HER2+', 'Comparing Therapies; Surgery vs. Chemotherapy', '', 'Patient was wondering why surgery is recommended before chemotherapy. Doctors may use chemotherapy if larger tumors are present to shrink the tumors before removal. More aggressive cancers are receptive to neoadjunctive chemotherapy. Having surgery first means that chemotherapy will be delayed until the wounds heal. ', 'Dhriti Bolangadi', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/821821', '', ''),
('Confused as why everyone seems to have surgery first', 'June 2014', '', '', 'Stage 2B ER/PR- HER2+', 'Comparing Therapies; Surgery vs. Chemotherapy', '', 'Neoadjuntive chemotherapy is used first with aggressive cancers. Sometimes, surgery is the only option for providing tissue for oncotype testing. Chemotherapy may be used to decrease tumor size before surgery. Depends on stage of cancer and center at which patient is getting treatment to determine if surgery or chemotherapy should be employed first.', 'Jo Kuramkote', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/821821', '', ''),
('Confused as why everyone seems to have surgery first', 'June 2014', 'Why do patients *not* use neoadjuvant chemotherapy?', '', 'Stage 2B, HR-, HER2+', 'Comparing Therapies; Surgery vs. Chemotherapy', '', 'Neoadjuvant therapy is often used for aggressive tumors including HER2+ and TNBC. Neoadjuvant treatment can help understand if tumor responds to the treatment being administered and can allow patient to do a less drastic surgery (lumpectomy vs. mastectomy)\n\nHaving surgery first means that chemotherapy will be delayed until the wounds heal. ', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/821821', '', ''),
('Does Oncotype apply on young women with larger tumor size?', 'April 2019', 'Patient needs help discering between chemotherapy and the use of Tamoxifen with no chemotherapy', 'I\'m 39 yrs old, IDC, 2.9cm, Grade 2, ER+/PR+/HER2-, Node 0/2, LVI present.', 'HR+, node-, LVI, Grade 2 IDC', 'Comparing Treatments ; Chemotherapy; Tamoxifen ', '', 'Results of TAILORx study shows that for the low and intermediate scores found a much lower rate of recurrence for those who had endocrine therapy only versus the previous studies. (NEEDS CONFIRMATION)', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/871059', '', ''),
('Does Oncotype apply on young women with larger tumor size?', 'April 17th, 2017', '', '', 'Stage II Breast Cancer, IDC', 'Comparing Treatments ; Chemotherapy; Tamoxifen ', '', 'The patient is at odds with deciding whether or not to begin chemo since her MO and another oncologist she consulted have differing opinions. Her MO thinks it would be best to do chemo after seeing her oncotype score, while the other oncologist belives with confidence that chemo is not necessary. She is feeling confused and pressured to make a decision soon so she does not miss the optimal time of initiating chemo. ', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/871059', '', ''),
('Does Oncotype apply on young women with larger tumor size?', 'April 17th, 2017', '', '', 'Stage II Breast Cancer', 'Comparing Treatments ; Chemotherapy; Tamoxifen ', '', 'The patient is 39 yrs, IDC, 2.9cm, grade2. Her oncotype came back with a score of 16, and 4% of distance occurrence at 9 years with AI or TAM along, and less than 1% chemotherapy benefit. Her MO and another oncologist had opposite opinion about whether she should do the chemotherapy. She was stuck and wanted to get some insight or suggestions as soon as possible to ensure that she would not miss the optimal time to initiate chemo if needed', 'Zihan Zheng', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/871059', '', ''),
('Can someone please help me understand my pathology report', 'December 2017', 'Patient has submitted pictures of her pathology report and wants help understanding the report', '', 'Stage II', 'Data Interpretation; Pathology Report', '', 'No insight', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/861206', '', ''),
('3 1/2 years post cancer', '', '', '', 'Stage II breast cancer', 'Encouragement', '', 'Diagnosed with stage 2 in left breast After 8 rounds of chemo ,I opted for a double mastestomy. That would be the best option for my peace of mind. In August of 2010 I had my Double mastectomy and that was pure torture. My firsr reconstruction job did not go so well. I developed uniboob. I am on Arimex. The body aches from it feel like flue but excercising works. I even ran a 5k in last May. But my ankles keep getting weeker and I can no longer wear high heels. I have very high arches so my balance is totally off now.I have kept my hair really short as it helps deal with hot flashes. I do not feel feminine anymore.  I am already on an antidepressant for the hot flashes. ', 'Emmanuel Akabogu', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/811906', '', ''),
('3 1/2 years post cancer', 'September 2013', 'I have no self control and cancer has ruinedmy life.I am 47. My daughter is 14 and I keep thinking how in a few years when she leaves for college I will be all alone. I don\'t want to take any more medications.I cannot concentrate and can barely keep my place clean. I feel so lost. Does anyone feel the same way?', '', '-', 'Encouragement', '', 'Consider psychological counseling or find other patients when feeling depressed, anxious, OCD', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/811906', '', ''),
('a little freaked out-can you help me off the ledge????', '', '', '', 'Stage 2A', 'Encouragement', '', 'Patients experienced lung sicknesses- bronchitis, pnemonia, allergies, sinus issues; got tests done and everything is clear, patient worried about how it will affect cancer. Patient dynamics include: ER+ / PR+, HER2-, HER2+ ', 'Christina Ton ', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/820720', '', ''),
('a little freaked out-can you help me off the ledge????', 'May \'14', '', '', 'Stage 2A, grade 2', 'Encouragement', '', 'Patient does not seem to have any cancer related symptoms. ', 'Preetham Ramesh', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/820720', '', ''),
('a little freaked out-can you help me off the ledge????', '', 'I have ongoing cough and now fatigue. I am really stressed out', '', 'Stage II', 'Encouragement', '', 'No insights', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/820720', '', ''),
('Anxiety at year since dx', '', '', '', 'Stage IIA, Grade 2, HER2-, ILC, ER+/PR+, 0/4 nodes', 'Encouragement', '', 'Longterm anxiety after diagnosis. Does anyone else experience anxiety year(s) after initial diagnosis?', 'Harrison Klinski', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/834503', '', ''),
('Anxiety at year since dx', '', '', '', '', 'Encouragement', '', 'Patients has been having anxiety since the diagnosis, between surgeries and her kids starting school again. She has had her ovaries removed and started hormonal therapy. Claims that family has moved on which she is glad to hear but is lonely when she is sad.', 'Jaspreet Deol', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/834503', '', ''),
('Anxiety at year since dx', '', '', '', 'Stage IIA, Grade 2, ER+/PR+, HER-; post-prophylactic ovary removal; taking Arimidex; pre-exchange surgery', 'Encouragement', '', 'Having anxiety after DX is normal and it takes time for it to decrease', 'Pooja Kaur Gill', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/834503', 'Follow up on mental health issues as side effects of Arimidex?', ''),
('Anxiety at year since dx', 'August 2015', 'Patient has the 1 year anniversary coming up for her DX and is feeling anxious', '', 'Stage II', 'Encouragement', '', 'Anxiety around (Dx) anniversaries is normal. Family members often \'move on\' as treatment continues and it can be lonely. ', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/834503', '', ''),
('Bad news days before chemo ends.', '', '', '', 'Stage IIB', 'Encouragement', '', 'Don\'t despair and move on. HER2+ might actually provide more therapies. ', 'Hamza Hussain', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/864544', '', ''),
('Bad news days before chemo ends.', 'May 2018', 'Patient was mis-diagnosed based on a mis placed file and is now in a comparatively worst considtion and is looking for advice and guidance', '', 'Stage II; HER2+ (misdiagnosed as HER2-)', 'Encouragement', '', 'While AC is not a HER2 inhibitor and hence not optimal for HER2+ cancer, it is still a good treatment for HER2+. ', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/864544', '', ''),
('CT Scan for Radiation Found Mass in Other Breast', 'July 2017', '', '', 'Stage IIA Grade 1', 'Encouragement', '', 'CT scan showed a mass in the other breast which the mammogram did not show. Potentially lymphedema, but MO is not concerned with the swelling.', 'Dhriti Bolangadi', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/858149', '', ''),
('CT Scan for Radiation Found Mass in Other Breast', 'July 2017', '', '', 'Stage 2A Grade 1', 'Encouragement', '', 'CT Scan for radiation found a potentially cancerous mass in the other breast of a patient that a mammogram failed to pick up. Patient\'s RO suspects lymphedema but patient\'s MO did not find swelling concerning. ', 'Jo Kuramkote', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/858149', '', ''),
('Emotions regarding last chemo', 'January 2014', 'Patient is emotional leading up to the last chemotherapy and is looking for encouragement and postive words', '', '-', 'Encouragement', '', 'No insights', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/817248', '', ''),
('Emotions regarding last chemo', 'Jan 24th, 2014', '', '', 'Stage II Breast Cancer', 'Encouragement', '', 'This patient is going to recieve her last chemo session as is feeling emotional about it and is seeking patients to share if they had similar feelings. She believes she is emotional because she is happy that chemicals willl no longer entering her body. This indicates that she is emotional in a posotive way. Many patients are excited for whats to come after chemo is done like enjoying food again and growing out their hair. ', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/817248', '', ''),
('Emotions regarding last chemo', 'Jan 23th, 2014', '', '', 'Stage II Breast Cancer', 'Encouragement', '', 'The patient was going to have her last chemo session. She was really emotional to it. She looked fowards to finishing the chemo but she also felt upset when thinking about it. Other patients reported similar feelings and encouraged her to do hormone therapy or rads to reduce recurrence.', 'Zihan Zheng', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/817248', '', ''),
('Feel like I\'ve been given a death sentence...', 'October 2015', '', 'DCIS, 3.5cm, ER/PR -, grade 3, BRCA1 +', 'Stage 2B ', 'Encouragement', '', 'There will be bad days and there will be days where you\'ll feel like its the end even during the treatement. The best way is to have a support system and make sure to soldier through the difficulty. There are people who bounce back from worst conditions so there is a clear proof that cancer is not a death sentence. DO NOT look at the Stage 4 Forum as it will only make you think more negatively and the key is to stay positive through this. Regarding alcohol use, discuss this with your MO as they can give an accurate reccomendation. ', 'Hamza Hussain', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/836235', '', ''),
('Feel like I\'ve been given a death sentence...', 'October 28, 2015', '', '', 'Stage II BC, DCIS, Left, 3cm, Stage 0, Grade 3', 'Encouragement', '', 'The patient was diagnosed with DCIS and before she had a lumpectomy, she found out she was BRCA1 positive so her surgery was changed to a bmx. Her pathology results came back and one of the 7 nodes came back positive. She feels helpless and very honestly replies that she expects to be gone in 10 years. She does not know what she should be putting her efforts in at the moment since she does not know if there is a point. She said she will try to have a better attitude tomorrow. She recieves a lot of feedback from others stating that with time she will feel better and more in control once she finds more out about her situation. ', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/836235', '', ''),
('Feel like I\'ve been given a death sentence...', 'October 2015', 'Patient is worried about her rapidly increasing stage of breast cancer and is looking for encouragement ', '', 'DCIS, HR-, BRCA1+, HER2?, Node+', 'Encouragement', '', '', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/836235', '', ''),
('Feels like it never ends...', 'May 2014', 'Patient feels that she is in a downward spiral with getting new issues ever since she got shingles and is looking for encouragement ', '', 'Stage II Breast Cancer', 'Encouragement', '', 'Patient feels that she is in a downward spiral with getting new issues ever since she got shingles such as allergies and aches. She applied head and ice and is planning on getting physical therapy to help with these issues', 'Deepthi Mohanraj', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/821008', '', ''),
('Feels like it never ends...', 'May 12th, 2014', '', '', 'Stage II Breast Cancer', 'Encouragement', '', 'Patient resolved respiratory problems with neti, but is starting to feel back aches and other issues. Aspirin helps and patient also ices frequently to reduce pain. Plans on getting a prescription for physical therapy and feels like she is falling apart from all the issues.', 'Devansh Dwivedy', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/821008', '', ''),
('Feels like it never ends...', 'May 12th, 2016', '', '', 'Stage II Breast Cancer', 'Encouragement', '', 'The patient felt like she was in a downward spiral- she kept geting new health problems: femora, shingles, bronchitis, allergies and now the back problem. She felt hard to fight back.', 'Zihan Zheng', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/821008', '', ''),
('Finding Support? Where? We Did/Do Have Cancer, Right?', 'May 18th 2014', '', 'Patient feels that bringing up her problems in a cancer support group would be out of place because the other women their are more advanced in their cancer stage and she feels that it wouldn\'t be appropriate for her to bring up, though the other women are perfectly kind and open to her. She wants to bring up TE\'s and redness in her breast. ', 'Stage II Breast Cancer', 'Encouragement', '', 'Other commentators said they agree with this and this is why they like using the breast cancer site, since the advice there is much more specific to issues and its easier to find people with the same issues. One person also reccomended a church support group and talking to the doctors or a patient advocate about issues.', 'Devansh Dwivedy', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/821180', '', ''),
('Finding Support? Where? We Did/Do Have Cancer, Right?', 'May 18, 2014', '', '', 'Stage II BC, DCIS, Right, 2 cm, Stage 0, Grade 3, 0/3 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'Encouragement', '', 'Many patients use the breast cancer site because they can get specific advice from people that are at the same stages of treatment as they are. The site provides them with a variety of topics that they can discuss. If the patient lives in a big city they are recommended to ask their clinic for different groups meeting in the area. A church support group is also another option as well as going to their doctor or surgeon where they can recommend a patient advocate.', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/821180', '', ''),
('Finding Support? Where? We Did/Do Have Cancer, Right?', '', 'Patient is looking for suport through the website after not feeling the support from local support groups', '', '', 'Encouragement', '', 'Its important to find a group with patients who have similar stage of cancer.', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/821180', '', ''),
('Gallbladder surgery... Liver mets chances?', 'January 26th 2016', 'Patient has a gallbladder surgery soon and is uncertain about changes making her more susecptible to liver mets.', '', 'Stage 2 breast cancer', 'Encouragement', '', 'One responder said that gallbladder removal doesn\'t make liver metastasis more likely, which is the main patient insight. Another mentioned that gallbladder problems can be due to side effects of PPI\'s, so patient should be sure she needs to remove the gallbladder and that is not due to a side effect of something else.', 'Devansh Dwivedy', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/840709', '', ''),
('Gallbladder surgery... Liver mets chances?', 'January 26, 2016', '', '', 'Stage II, IDC, 1cm, Stage IIA, Grade 2, 3/12 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'Encouragement', '', '3 year remition. Patient Paranoid about liver metastisis caused by gallbladder pain. Ultrasounds/CT scan would show possiple liver metastasis problems and gallstones. Gallplabber removal does not directly cooralte to liver metastasis.', 'Harrison Klinski', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/840709', '', ''),
('Gallbladder surgery... Liver mets chances?', 'January 26, 2016', '', '', 'IDC, Stage IIA BC, Grade 2, 3 1/2 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'Encouragement', '', 'The patient is a BC survivor and is feeling anxious about having gallblaldder surgery due to the changes in her body that can make her more susceptible to liver mets. She is seeking to hear success stories to giver a peice of mind, going into her surgery. One patient had their gallbladder removed five years after they were treated for 2B BC. To this day she reports to be in good health, with her mammogram to be clear and her tumor marker test was the lowes it has ever been. ', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/840709', '', ''),
('Hi, I guess after today\'s app\'t I was in the wrong group!', 'August 30th, 2014', 'Patient has been getting treated and is been dealing with the side effects and is mainly looking for encouragement ', 'Patient had lumpectomy and a lymph node removed. Patient has Stage 2 grade 3 IDC, is starting chemo, and their physician wants more lymph nodes removed.', 'Stage 2 Breast Cancer', 'Encouragement', '', 'Patient had to stop her work in childcare after chemo due to risk of infection from children, leading to money problems. Reccomendations were to watch out for lymphedema, accept helps from friends/family/neighbors, accepting that it is best to not do work while fighting cancer, and buying pre-made food to try to keep home life relatively stress free.', 'Devansh Dwivedy', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/824094', '', ''),
('Hi, I guess after today\'s app\'t I was in the wrong group!', 'August 29, 2014', '', '', 'Stage II BC, IDC, grade 3', 'Encouragement', '', 'Although it may be tough to quit a job after a diagnosis, it is best to do so especially in a job involving germ exposure. With increasing financial costs it is helpful to allow people to help. You have to remember that you are not weak just because you cannot work. It is also helpful to think of obstacles as \"small hurdles\"\" to not get overwhelmed. \"', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/824094', '', ''),
('Hi, I guess after today\'s app\'t I was in the wrong group!', '', '', '', 'Stage II Breast Cancer', 'Encouragement', '', 'Pt diagnosed with more lumps after initial lymph node removals and now has to enter chemo therapy. Due to this, pt is having to miss her work, causing a financial shortage. Pt is recieving donations but isn\'t enjoying how the cancer is effecting their day to day life.', 'Geon Kim', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/824094', '', ''),
('How have friendships changed for you?', 'November 2014', 'Patient is asking about how people\'s relationships chnage after they get diagnosed with cancer', '', '', 'Encouragement', '', 'Different people handle things differently. Some friends will be very understanding and easy to talk to about cancer. Others will be awkard and open. This is usually not because they are insensitive, but because they don\'t know what to say and are uncomfortable with the situation. In this case, it\'s important to give them some time to acclimate as it is hard to see a friend diagnosed with cancer. It is normal for relationships with family and friends to change but it is important to let them run their course. ', 'Preetham Ramesh', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/825995', '', ''),
('How have friendships changed for you?', 'November 3, 2014', '', '', 'IDC, Stage IIB, Grade 3, 3/22 nodes, ER-/PR-, HER2-', 'Encouragement', '', 'The best thing to do when navigating relationships during cancer treatment, is to not expect all your family and friends to be there for you like you expect them to be. Some of them will not know what to say or act which is okay, because it is important to remember that this is new territory  for them as well. It is also okay to allow relationships to run their course because it is only natural. ', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/825995', '', ''),
('How have friendships changed for you?', 'November 3rd/ 2014', '', '', 'Stage 2 BC', 'Encouragement', '', 'Her relationship with friends and families changed a lot throughout her treatment of cancer. She did not get enough support from those who she wanted support from. Bur at the same time, she made new friends and she was thankful to that.', 'Zihan Zheng', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/825995', '', ''),
('Life Of a Journey How Do I do it all again', 'March 7, 2015', 'Patient has just been diagnosed and is looking for encouragement ', '', 'Stage IIA BC, IDC, Grade 3', 'Encouragement', '', 'It would be helpful to know the treatment plan with your oncologist to alleviate some anxiety. Something to consider is that people may not even need chemo, just surgery and even a chemo alternative which is known as \"chemo lite.\"\" Having this site to have people to talk to can help with the emotional/ mental aspects of having to go through cancer. \"', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/829245', '', ''),
('Life Of a Journey How Do I do it all again', 'March 8, 2015', 'Patient seeking advice on fighting cancer for the second time', 'Previously diagnosed with childhood cancer, stage 4', 'Stage II BC, Grade 3', 'Encouragement', '', 'Seeking breast cancer forums such as community.breastcancer.org is a great way to share your experiences with others a find support. It is a good idea to express your previous treatment for childhood cancer to your doctors so they understand your fears and concerns so they can help you better through your journey as well.', 'Abigail Mendoza', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/829245', '', ''),
('looking for long term survivors diagnosed young', 'March 11. 2018', 'Patient is looking for encouragement from patients diagonsed at a young age', '', 'Stage IIA, DCIS/IDC, Right, Grade 2, 0/1 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'Encouragement', '', 'It is important to remember that as a nurse one is only exposed to the patients who are sick which is why they are back in the hospital, therefore it is important to remember that your experience can be different. Since the drugs arent helping, it is recommended to consider an oopherectomy and taking AI (aromatase inhibitors). Although the patient is young, it is something to consider since it will reduce the estrogen level by 80%. A patient tried this treatment and says it is tolerable.', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/863150', '', ''),
('Lump discovered while on chemo', 'Dec 14, 2015', '', 'Patient has had lumpectomy, lymph node removal, mastectomy, reconstruction and chemo.', 'Stage IIA, Grade 3, Right, 2cm, 0/12 nodes, ER-/PR-, HER2-', 'Encouragement', '', 'Patient thinks she feels a lump again where her fibroadenoma was previously removed and worries that new cancer has grown during chemo. It is likely scar tissue, but have an ultrasound to check.', 'Valerie Chen', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/838496', '', ''),
('Completely freaked myself out', '', '', '', 'Stage IIA, Grade 2,', 'Encouragement ', '', 'Patients report radiology reports always state the worst case scenerio and things are usually not as bad as they are reported. ', 'Hamza Hussain', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/821475', '', ''),
('Completely freaked myself out', 'October 2008', '', '', 'Stage IIA, Grade 2,', 'Encouragement ', '', 'Radiologists usually give patients the worst case scenario for liability reasons and also as motivation to investigate more. However, things are usually better than they might seem.', 'Preetham Ramesh ', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/821475', '', ''),
('Completely freaked myself out', 'Oct. 2008', '', '', 'Stage IIA, Grade 2,', 'Encouragement ', '', 'Patient has been \"freaking herself out\"\" about her thyroid biopsy next week. A radiologist wants to check on califications', ' the patient is worried even though 95% are benign. Patients stated that radiologists often describe the worst possible scenarios to \"\"cover their butt\"\" in case of a missed diagnosis\"', 'Sharan K. G.', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/821475', ''),
('Completely freaked myself out', 'May 2014', 'Patient is worried about her thyroid biopsy as the radiologists are checking for calcification even when 95% are benign', '', '-', 'Encouragement ', '', '(Tangential insight?) Radiologists typically give the worst case scenario for liability and to promote further exploration', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/821475', '', 'This relates to nervousness about a secondary site biopsy (not related to breast cancer). Tangential insight worth following up on '),
('CT Scan for Radiation Found Mass in Other Breast', 'August 2017', 'I just have a sense of dread because I might have tumor in my other breast and might also have lymphedema. I\'m not mentally ready for this. I guess I just needed to vent.', '', '-', 'Encouragement ', '', 'No insights', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/858149', '', ''),
('Delayed Mamoprint Results', 'September 2015', '', '', 'Stage II Breast Cancer', 'Encouragement; Comparing Therapies; Mamoprint vs. Oncotype Tests', '', 'The patient was concerned about the difference in opinion between her surgeon and oncologist. The surgeon wanted a Mamoprint but the oncologist wanted oncotype tests. The Mamoprint was done to speed up the results but it was actually canceled due to the discrepancies between the surgeon and the oncologist. The patient was advised to set up a conversation with both doctors before moving forward with treatment. ', 'Deepthi Mohanraj', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/835157', '', ''),
('Delayed Mamoprint Results', 'September 2015', '', '', 'Stage II Breast Cancer', 'Encouragement; Comparing Therapies; Mamoprint vs. Oncotype Tests', '', 'Patient was concerned due to discrepencies between the masectomay surgeon and oncologist over the type of testing she would need, either the mamoprint or oncotype test, of which she believed the mamoprint would provide results sooner. Oncotype tests give a larger scale than Mamoprint tests, but Onctoype is applicable to positive Estrogen Receptors (ER), whereas Mamoprint is to positive and negative ERs.', 'Kylie Helton', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/835157', '', ''),
('Delayed Mamoprint Results', 'September 21st, 2015', 'Mamoprint results are taking 1 month to process due to discrepansies between the breast surgeon and oncologist. Patient inquires on how to deal with the situation moving forwards or maybe prevent it from happening again.', 'Stage II with extensive lymphatic invasion', 'unknown', 'Encouragement; Comparing Therapies; Mamoprint vs. Oncotype Tests', '', 'Just reccomended that moving forward have meetings with your doctors to set clear goals and guidelines. Make sure everyone is on the same page to help you fight the cancer. ', 'Sarah Taga', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/835157', '', ''),
('Delayed Mamoprint Results', '-', 'I\'m frustrated with the long delay to get my Mammaprint results which has impacted when I can get back to work. I am venting. ', '-', '-', 'Encouragement; Comparing Therapies; Mamoprint vs. Oncotype Tests', '', 'No insights', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/835157', '', ''),
('Can\'t sleep...1:45am. Sigh...', 'September 2014', '', '', 'Stage 2A', 'Encouragement; Lung Nodules', '', 'Patient is worried about her lung nodules being cancerous and is losing sleeping thinking about it. Other patients encourage that most nodules are not cancerous and many people get them. The takeaway was to prioritze sleep and not worry about something until it becomes an actual problem. ', 'Jo Kuramkote', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/824569', '', ''),
('Can\'t sleep...1:45am. Sigh...', 'Sept. 2014', '', '', 'Stage IIA', 'Encouragement; Lung Nodules', '', 'Subject just had her last nuerasta shot, and is still undergoing chemo. Patients often have trouble going to sleep because of stress. They are often very worried about possible metasteses of their cancer. In this thread, patients discussed nodules on their lungs that came up in their scans', 'Sharan K. G.', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/824569', '', ''),
('It is papillary thyroid carcinoma', 'June 11, 2014', '', '', 'Stage IIA Thyroid Cancer, ILC, 2cm, Grade 2, 0/1 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'Encouragement; Misdiagnosis', '', 'Many experiences from having this type of cancer come out as positive since they too have been told it is completely curable. There are different ways that this can be diagnosed or show symptoms. One patient was diagnosed bc they had excessive coughing. On another patient, they found thyroid nodules by accident during a breast MRI. ', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/821880', '', ''),
('It is papillary thyroid carcinoma', 'June 11, 2014', 'Patient is looking for positive affirmations after being diagnosed with papillary thyroid carcinoma.', 'ILC, 2cm, Grade 2. 0/1 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'Stage 2A ', 'Encouragement; Misdiagnosis', '', 'Patients have reported getting misdiagnosed with thyroid carcinoma.  Patients also have said that these are very common and easily treateble. ', 'Hamza Hussain', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/821880', '', ''),
('just diagnosed MRI tomorrow', 'January 10, 2019', 'Patient is asking how physcians will be able to tell if the cancer has not spread to other body parts just through a MRI', '', 'Stage IIA, Grade 2, 0/2 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'Encouragement; MRI', '', 'The breast MRI is the best tool to use to see if there are any other tumors in the body. This tool gives your doctor the best information to determine the treatment plan best for you so it is best to take it one day at a time. A patient recommended that it is important remember that it is a long process and its a waiting game and although it may seen extremely urgent to us, its not. Before an MRI, it is suggested to take a Valium or Xanax to take the edge off and give you the opportunity to nap during it.', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/869269', '', ''),
('just diagnosed w/ Invasive ductal carcinoma with tubular', 'January, 11, 2019 ', 'Patient has just been diagnosed with invasive ductal carcinoma and is looking for encouragement ', '', 'Stage IIA, Grade 2, 0/2 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'Encouragement; Specific Condition; MRI', '', 'After a recent diagnosis, it is best to spend your time researching your options. The more one knows about the treatments offered, the most likely you will make the correct decision. The beginnning is the scariest part and once you know your plan, you\'ll feel a lot better. This is an important time for self care, so listening to music and dancing can help relieve anxiety. It is suggested to \"live in the present', ' as the future is not given to anyone.\"\" \"', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/869293', ''),
('How to make myself crazy trying to interpret tech statements', 'April 23rd, 2014', 'Patient is concerned about her tech\'s expressions during a recent x-ray and is worred and stressed . ', 'Patient was sick all winter with colds. Chest x-ray was clear. ', 'Stage 2 Breast Cancer', 'Encouragement; X-Rays', '', 'The patient tried to read her tech\'s expression after a most recent x-ray but couldn\'t, which meant that she was very worried and stressed about what came up on the x-ray. Another responder also mentioned being misled by the tech\'s facial expression into believing that her x-ray was normal, only to be told that she had cancer. Conclusion: patients shouldn\'t focus too much on their tech\'s faces for information on whether or not they have cancer or are normal, as this may lead to unnecessary or misleading stress.', 'Devansh Dwivedy', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/820451', '', ''),
('How to make myself crazy trying to interpret tech statements', 'April 23th/ 2014', '', 'Her has been sick for almost all winter with crazy colds. Things started to resolved since March, but still slowly going on.', 'Stage 2 BC', 'Encouragement; X-Rays', '', 'It can make a patient nervous and scared to try to interpret the mind and facial expression of the techs', '', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/820451', '', ''),
('How to make myself crazy trying to interpret tech statements', 'April 23, 2014', '', 'Patien has been sick with a cold almost all winter, so went in for an X-ray, got worried thinking something was wrong but it was clear. They still have the cough but it is significantly less. ', 'Stage IIA, ILC, 2 cm, Grade 2, 0/1 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'Encouragement; X-Rays', '', 'When patients go in for a scan, they try to read the expression of the techs which brings much anxiety since they can misinterpret or simply be unable to leading to spirilizing thoughts. It backfired on a patient and recieved bad news. It is important to not focus on the techs facial expressions, since it could lead to unesccesary anxiety.', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/820451', '', ''),
('Can\'t sleep...1:45am. Sigh...', 'September 2014', 'Patient is worried regarding two spots on her lungs is worried she will diagnosed with Sarcoma similar to her brother ', '', 'Stage II, lung nodules', 'Encouragement? OR Data Interpretation; Lung Nodules', '', 'Lung nodules are very common and not necessarily indicative of metastases', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/824569', '', ''),
('Any California girls out there starting chemo in the summer?', '6/4/2014', '', '', 'Stage 2A, ER+/PR-HER2- ', 'Inter-Personal Patient Connections', '', 'Patient finding new ways to reach out to patients with similar situations. Having no families or friends around makes going through treatment harder and more lonely. ', 'Christina Ton ', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/821674', '', ''),
('Any California girls out there starting chemo in the summer?', 'June 2014', '', '', '', 'Inter-Personal Patient Connections', '', 'Patient connects with other people in the area who are in the same position and understand what it is like to go through chemo in the summer and alone. They find ways of connecting such as through Facebook. ', 'Deepthi Mohanraj', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/821674', '', ''),
('Any California girls out there starting chemo in the summer?', '', '', '', 'DCIS, 3cm, Stage IIA, Grade 3, 0/4 nodes, ER+/PR-, HER2-', 'Inter-Personal Patient Connections', '', 'Conecting with other cancer patients (in California). Patient in need of companion who has been or is going through cancer diagnosis/treatment.', 'Harrison Klinski', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/821674', '', ''),
('Genetic Test Results are In', 'May 4th 2016', 'no patient query ', '', 'Stage 2 Breast Cancer', 'Inter-Personal Patient Connections', '', 'Patient is sharing her genetic test results but not really asking any questions. She had a genetic test and is BRCA1 and BRCA2 negative. No real patient insights.', 'Devansh Dwivedy', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/844014', '', ''),
('Genetic Test Results are In', 'May 4, 2016', '', '', 'Stage II, LC, Right, 5cm, Stage IIB, Grade 2, 1/1 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'Inter-Personal Patient Connections', '', 'No patient insights', 'Harrison Klinski', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/844014', '', ''),
('Genetic Test Results are In', 'May 2016', '', '45 years old, ', 'Stage 2 BC, ILC, Right, 5cm, Stage IIB, Grade 2, 1/1 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-, post-lumpectomy (right) and reconstruction (left)', 'Inter-Personal Patient Connections', '', 'No insights (primarily a patient sharing about her test results).', 'Kendall Vanderwouw', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/844014', '', ''),
('Looking for an expert', 'September 30, 2016', 'Patient is looking for physicians around Philadelphia', '', 'Stage II BC ', 'Inter-Personal Patient Connections', '', 'The link below was recommended to use when looking for a second opinon, which offers suggestions and provides a link to the National Cancer Institute\'s Comprehensive Cancer Centers around the country. John Hopkins in Baltimore also does long distance consultations. ', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/848555', '', ''),
('Diagnosed in 30s', 'November 16th, 2017', '', '', 'Stage IIA Breast Cancer', 'Inter-Personal Patient Connections; Early-Age Diagnosis', '', 'Patient is a mom of under 3 year-old kids at the time. She\'d like to connect to other women who have been through the same problem with her. She said that it was very difficult to stay positive for her children during her diagnosis. ', 'Duyen Nguyen', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/847088', '', ''),
('Diagnosed in 30s', '-', 'I want to connect with others who were diagnosed with breast cancer in their 30s.', '-', '-', 'Inter-Personal Patient Connections; Early-Age Diagnosis', '', 'No insights', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/847088', '', ''),
('Diagnosed in 30s', 'March 12, 2018', '', '', 'Stage IIA, IDC', 'Inter-Personal Patient Connections; Early-Age Diagnosis', '', 'Patient is a 34 year old mother with a two year old son. She sympathizes with the journey of finding out the diganoses. She communicates that she has come a long way after recieving 3/4 rounds of chemo. She believes this site has helped her since her diagnosis, which is why she has been on the forum ever since she discovered it. ', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/847088', '', ''),
('Diagnosed in 30s', 'December 10th, 2017', '', '', 'Stage II Breast Cancer', 'Inter-Personal Patient Connections; Early-Age Diagnosis', '', 'Patient was diagnosed with 2 affected nodes multi focal disease in breast, grade 3. She has 2 kids and she felt intense uncertainty during her treatment. She tried to focus on what she could to improve her health after treatment,', 'Zihan Zheng', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/847088', '', ''),
('Cold caps for hair loss with chemo treatment', 'November 2014', 'Can anyone in Scottsdale help me store cold caps?', '', '-', 'Interpersonal Patient Connections; Cold Caps', '', 'No insights', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/826034', '', ''),
('Caffeine...specifically soda during chemo? Yay or Nay?', 'July 2014', 'Patient is asking if consumption of soda during chemotherpay is a good idea. ', '', 'Stage II; undergoing chemotherapy', 'Lifestyle', '', 'Soda , which is diuretic, could be problematic with chemo which is cleared through kidneys. Could cause dehydration (INVESTIGATE)\n\nMost people gave up soda because of changed taste preferences', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/823340', '', ''),
('Alcohol use during treatment', 'September 2013', '', '', 'Stage II BC, taking A/C chemo', 'Lifestyle; Alcohol', '', 'Most oncologists are ok with a couple of glasses of wine a week during A/C chemo.Though most patient\'s dont have the appetite for it. ', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/811409', '', ''),
('20%+ Diagnosed Early-Stage Stop Follow-Up Care Early', 'April 16, 2019-April 17, 2019', '', '', 'Stage I, Stage II breast cancer', 'Other', '', '20% women with early breast cancer diagnosis stop follow-up appointments. Feesability and lack of confidence in provider discourage patient attendence/complience', 'Harrison Klinski, Shehryar Iqbal', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/871039', '', ''),
('20%+ Diagnosed Early-Stage Stop Follow-Up Care Early', 'April 2019', 'No query', '', 'Stage I and Stage II, post-treatment monitoring', 'Other', '', 'More Than 20% of Women Diagnosed With Early-Stage Breast Cancer Stop Follow-Up Care Early; some reasons include cost associated with visits and lack of faith in doctors.  ', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/871039', '', ''),
('Alcohol use during treatment', '', '', '', 'Stage II BC', 'Other', '', 'The patient is currently going through their second round of AC chemotherapy and wanted to know if alcohol consumption would affect her health. Most patients who are responding said that their oncologists recocomended no more than 1-2 drinks per week. The patients also experienced a lack of appetite (not many wanted to consume alcohol either) while on this regimen. ', 'Dhriti Bolangadi', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/811409', '', ''),
('Alcohol use during treatment', '', '', '', 'Stage II BC', 'Other', '', 'Some patients do not feel like having alcohol. Some physicians reccomend only 1-2 a week. ', 'Hamza Hussain', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/811409', '', ''),
('Alcohol use during treatment', '', '', '', 'Stage II Breast Cancer', 'Other', '', 'Patient is travelling and concern about alcohol. One or two cups of wines is okay according to an oncologist. However, the taste buds might change. Many people lose the taste for wine and said that wine is now tasting like vinegar.', 'Linh Nguyen', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/811409', '', ''),
('Almost 4 years breast cancer free and doctor won\'t do any tests', '', '', '', 'Stage II BC', 'Other', '', 'Doctors tend not to perform any scans unless there are symptoms that persist. Radiation exposure needs to stay minimal to prevent any new cases of proliferation.', 'Dhriti Bolangadi', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/822537', '', ''),
('Almost 4 years breast cancer free and doctor won\'t do any tests', '', '', '', 'Stage II BC', 'Other', '', 'Usually there are no scans done unless there are any symptoms. Minimal radiation is key.', 'Hamza Hussain ', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/822537', '', ''),
('Annual Bone Scans?', 'December 2017', '', '', 'Stage IIB Grade 3 Breast Cancer', 'Other', '', 'Annual bone scans are not recommended unless symptoms of pain in joints or other areas arise. The intent is to reduce exposure to extra radiation.', 'Dhriti Bolangadi', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/827050', '', ''),
('Annual Bone Scans?', '', '', '', 'Stage IIA Breast Cancer', 'Other', '', 'Patient gets bone scans every year, it has been 4 years since diagnosis. Oncologyst had said a bone scan is not neccessary because there are no symptoms of bone mets, no aches or pains.', 'Jaspreet Deol', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/827050', '', ''),
('Annual Bone Scans?', 'December 2014', 'Patient is asking if anyone has yearly bone scans. ', '', 'Stage II, post-treatment completion', 'Other', '', 'Annual bone scans after completion of treatment not recommended in the absence of symptoms', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/827050', '', ''),
('Best oncologist in minnesota', 'March 2016', '', '', 'Stage II BC', 'Other', '', 'Patient needed help locating best oncologist in their area.', 'Dhriti Bolangadi', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/842548', '', ''),
('Caffeine...specifically soda during chemo? Yay or Nay?', 'July 2014', '', '', 'Stage IIA; undergoing chemotherapy', 'Other', '', 'Soda may be harmful to kidneys during chemo. Possible enhancement of bone depletion and cell damage. Potential risk of dehydration. Try replacing soda with plain water, unsweetened iced tea, lemonade, seltzer in fruit juice. Soda may not taste good in mouth during chemo.', 'Pooja Kaur Gill', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/823340', '', ''),
('Caffeine...specifically soda during chemo? Yay or Nay?', 'August 2014', '', '', 'Stage 2A BC', 'Other', '', '', 'Sagel Ejantkar ', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/823340', '', ''),
('Caffeine...specifically soda during chemo? Yay or Nay?', 'August 2014', '', '', 'Stage IIA, IDC BC, right, 4cm, Grade 1, ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'Other', '', 'Patient is requesting insight on the pros and cons of consuming diet soda while undergoing chemotherapy. Many say they lost their appetite for soda and their sweet tooth so they did not consume it. Since diet soda can be very dehydrating it is not recommended to soley consume it. Many of the side effects of diet soda can affect a person on chemo in a stronger way. For example, chemo was found to damage teeth and so does diet soda. ', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/823340', '', ''),
('How cancer spreads?', 'Feb11 2015', 'Patient is inquiring if BC spreads to the lymph nodes or to other organs', '', 'Stage 2 Breast Cancer', 'Other', '', 'Cancer cells are always in the body\'s bloodstream, and may stay dormant or may awaken later. If its not in the lymph nodes, this reduces the chance of it coming back, but cancer can spread even without lymph node involvement, as the cells are almost certainly always present. Prognosis for cancer returning is the same whether its found early or when the patient becomes symptomatic. Its best to focus on the present and not worry about what ifs.', 'Devansh Dwivedy', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/828400', '', ''),
('How cancer spreads?', '', '', '', 'BC', 'Other', '', 'Cancer can metastasize via the blood stream, lymphatic system or regionally to nearby tissue. Therefore, lymph node involvement is not always the next stage of BC.', 'Preetham Ramesh', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/828400', '', ''),
('How cancer spreads?', 'February 11, 2015', '', '', 'Stage IIA BC, IDC, 2cm, Grade 3, 0/3 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'Other', '', 'There are cancer cells in the lymphatic system and in the bloodstream, which may be domant and have the possibility to become active in the future at any point. As of right now, the biotechnology behind trying to detect small cancer cells is too complicated. It is suggested to focus on your health at this stage and let the rest work itself out. Having routine scans once a year helps minimize anxiety. ', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/828400', '', ''),
('Let\'s stand as one we must unite to cure breast cancer !', 'August 10, 2015', '', '', 'Stage IV BC, ER+/PR+/ HER2- ', 'Other', '', 'The color black is recommeneded to wear instead of pink to show that organizations tend to not be clear with the true statistics of cancer. They do not show the dark reality of having cancer as it usually progresses even after an early diagnosis and its likelihood to come back. \"Pink washing\"\" is believed to be done by the media. \"', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/834122', '', ''),
('Let\'s stand as one we must unite to cure breast cancer !', 'August 2015', 'Does wearing pink, a color traditionally representing coddling, misrepresent the pain and loss of cancer?', 'Right, Stage IV, ER+/PR+, HER2- (FISH)', 'Stage II BC (although many of the commenters had later Stage IV recurrences)', 'Other', '', 'Patients recommend using the color black to represent cancer in the media and through expression, rather than pink (which tends to cast a rosy hue on the misery of cancer). Patients also warn that the media fails to address how many of stage IV patients previously had Stage I or II cancer.', 'Kendall Vanderwouw', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/834122', '', ''),
('Cold caps for hair loss with chemo treatment', 'November 2014', '', '', 'Stage II breast cancer', 'Other; Cold Caps', '', 'Patient is wondering about the effectiveness of cold caps and how to travel with the cooler and caps. ', 'Dhriti Bolangadi', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/826034', '', ''),
('Cold caps for hair loss with chemo treatment', 'November 2014', '', '', 'Stage II breast cancer', 'Other; Cold Caps', '', 'Patient is wondering how to store cold caps during travel to chemo treatments and is directed to a thread \"Help Me Get Through Treatment\"\" that details how to handle cold caps.\"', 'Jo Kuramkote', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/826034', '', ''),
('Change Diet', 'March 2014', '', '', 'Stage II BC', 'Other; Diet', '', 'Many patients begin to eat more health such as avoiding sugar and alcohol. If people decide to become vegetarian it is important that they get enough protein and iron to help make new cells. ', 'Deepthi Mohanraj', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/819032', '', ''),
('Change Diet', '', '', '', 'Stage II BC', 'Other; Diet', '', 'For detailed outline of dietary plans refer to the following books: \"The Anti Cancer:  A New Way of Life\"\" and \"\"Foods That Fight Cancer\"\". Other patients have reduced their in take of alcohol and red meat to switch to a more vegetarian diet. Patients also reccomended getting enough protein and iron. \"', 'Hamza Hussain', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/819032', '', ''),
('Change Diet', '', '', '', 'Stage II BC', 'Other; Diet', '', 'Patients recommend eating healthy and avoiding alcohol but in moderation, not total abstinence. Most agree that a healthier diet can mitigate cancer symptoms but not entirely prevent onset of breast cancer.', 'Jo Kuramkote', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/819032', '', ''),
('Can someone please help me understand my pathology report', 'December 30th, 2017', '', '', 'Stage 2a breast cancer', 'Other; Pathology Report', '', 'Patient listed their pathology report and responder interpreted it. Not much more here.', 'Devansh Dwivedy', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/861206', '', ''),
('Can someone please help me understand my pathology report', '', '', '', 'Stage II BC', 'Other; Pathology Report', '', 'It is IDC with DCIS and clean margins. 1 lymph node +, ER+, PR+, HER2+. The ki-67 score is moderate and it matches the grade 2 Dx from sigline', 'Hamza Hussain', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/861206', '', ''),
('Hello- trying to understand pathology report', 'Dec 2017', 'Patient is looking to undetstand her pathology report', '', 'Breast Cancer II', 'Other; Pathology Report', '', 'Pt underwent chemotherapy, masterectomy, and radiation therapy and wants to understand her pathology report.', 'Geon Kim', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/860803', '', ''),
('Hello- trying to understand pathology report', '', '', '', 'Stage 2 Breast cancer ', 'Other; Pathology Report', '', 'Patient underwent radiation, masectomy and chemo. Wanting a clearer report on pathology report.', 'Jaspreet Deol', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/860803', '', ''),
('Hello- trying to understand pathology report', 'Dec 2017', '', '', 'Breast Cancer Stage 2A with 2 lymph nodes ', 'Other; Pathology Report', '', 'Obtain second opinion from breast cancer pathologists - they often have differing opinions ', 'Kelvin Du ', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/860803', '', ''),
('Help deciphering pathology report', 'August 2017', '', '', 'Stage II Breast Cancer, Mucinous Carcinoma patient reconsidering chemotherapy after surgery ', 'Other; Pathology Report', '', 'Patient had surgical procedure for a masectomy. Patient could not clearly understand the pathology of the report from the lesions that were made during surgery. Patient is unsure if they should continue Chemotherapy because of a 20 oncotype.', 'Amen Aiwekhoe ', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/857701', '', ''),
('Help deciphering pathology report', 'August 6th/ 2017', '', 'Her surgeon said that there were some cancer closer to skin that she expected, so she removed more kin than she planned on to test that. ', 'Stage 2 BC', 'Other; Pathology Report', '', 'The removal of more skin than expected my result in the extension of cancers to the medical resection borders.', 'Zihan Zheng', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/857701', '', ''),
('Help deciphering pathology report', 'August 5, 2017', '', '', 'Stage II Breast Cancer, Mucinous Carcinoma (10 cm long strip of multiple small tumors inleft breast) ER+ (87%) PR-, HER2-', 'Other; Pathology Report', '', 'The confusion from the pathology report was later clarified once the patient realized that their surgeon said there was some cancer closer to the skin than they expected which explains the lesions said in the pathology report. It is recommended to call their doctors office to get an explanantion to alleviate some anxiety. ', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/857701', '', ''),
('DIEP flap vs other reconstruction', 'March 26th, 2018', '', '', 'Stage 1A ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'Other; Reconstruction', '', 'Reccomend the DIEP flap because it feels more natural and surgeon was able to match breatss nicely. To prevent noticeable scarring go with skin sparing. Ask as questions about nipple reconstruction, and make sure that your breast surgeon and your plastic surgeon are aware and understand each others paths.', 'Sarah Taga', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/863508', '', ''),
('DIEP flap vs other reconstruction', 'March 25th, 2018 ', '', '', 'Stage 2B, ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'Other; Reconstruction', '', 'Talk to your surgeons and figure out whats best for you particularly, sk about skin and nipple sparing and how it can affect your reconstruction. Tissue expanders for reconstruction can be uncomfortable, with the DIEP flap your pectoral muscles feel more normal.', 'Sarah Taga', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/863508', '', ''),
('DIEP flap vs other reconstruction', 'March 2018', 'Is DIEP flap surgery with reconstruction a good option for me?', '', 'Stage II with unilateral mastectomy', 'Other; Reconstruction', '', 'DIEP flap surgery has several advantages including being natural. \n\nIt can be done alongside mastectomy or after. \n\nIt is important to consult with a plastic surgeon prior to mastectomy and come up with a plan together with the surgeon', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/863508', '', ''),
('DIEP flap vs other reconstruction', 'March 25th, 2018', '', '', 'Stage II Breast Cancer', 'Other; Reconstruction', '', 'Patient had a unilateral mastectomy on right breast. She would have reconstruction, but she wanted a natural, real feel without anything unnatural in her body with a potential of rupture or complication.', 'Zihan Zheng', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/863508', '', ''),
('If 93% survival rate at 5 yrs - why do the 7% perish?', '2.8/ 2015', 'Patient is asking if a 93% survival rate is mentioned, where does the 7% go from this estimate', '', 'Stage 2 BC', 'Other; Survival Rate', '', 'Althoug there is a roughly 93% survival rate for stage 2b breast cancer, there is still a very small percent chance of perish.This is because even though the cancer was discovered early, it either does not respond to treatment or was aggressive enough to attack a major organ and cause death.', 'Zihan Zheng', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/828285', '', ''),
('If 93% survival rate at 5 yrs - why do the 7% perish?', 'February 8, 2015', '', '', 'Stage IIB, IDC, Right, 2 cm, Grade II, ER+/PR+, HER2+ (IHC)', 'Other; Survival Rate', '', 'Many believe that the other 7% went through another accident that may have caused death or that they were never stage II to begin with. They must have been misdiagnosed and were actually stage IV and didnt realize it until it was too late or they became \"metastatic\"\" and later passed away from it. \"', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/828285', '', ''),
('If 93% survival rate at 5 yrs - why do the 7% perish?', 'February 8, 2015', 'Patient is asking if her cancer presents with a 93% survival rate, what happens to the other 7%?', 'IDS Stage IIB Grade 2 ER+/PR+ HER2-', 'IDC Stage IV Grade 3', 'Other; Survival Rate', '', 'The reason for the 7% is due to multiple things, patients could develop secondaries or their condition can progress further after treatment. Patients could die from unrelated reasons such as heart attacks or car accidents. Patients could also stop treatment for various reasons.', 'Sarah Taga', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/828285', '', ''),
('Decisions re: ovaries/estrogen', '', '', '', '', 'Others\' Experience', '', 'VERY COMPLICATED :) :)', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/821080', '', ''),
('Looking for Advice', 'Feb 2019', '', '', 'Stage II breast cancer ', 'Others\' Experience', '', 'Get full mastectomy to prevent recurrence and spreading of cancer. Ask physician about Oncotype test for patients who are node-positive called Oncotype DX Breast Recurrence Score Micromets and Node Positive which helps detect how the cancer may respond to treatment. Another option is to ask doctor about the EndoPredict Test which can predict the risk of distant recurrence of early-stage, hormone-receptor-positive, HER2-negative breast cancer that is either node-negative or has up to three positive lymph nodes.', 'Pooja Kaur Gill', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/870003', '', 'Appropriate use of Oncotype DX'),
('Low WBC months after chemo. Do I need a bone marrow biopsy ?', '', 'Patient is scared regarding a drop in her WBC score after surgery, radiation and tamoxifen', '', '[Post chemotherapy OR Post radiation OR Post tamoxifen]', 'Others\' Experience', ' Low WBC, Bone Marrow Biopsy', 'WBC can be lower after treatment (such as Chemotherapy & Herceptin) but they do recover. In some cases, bone marrow biopsy could uncover other causes such as leukemia. ', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/824728', '', ''),
('Lymph vascular indeterminate', 'Mar 1, 2016', '', 'Patient has had lymph node removal, mastectomy, ovary removal, reconstruction, and chemo.', 'Stage IIA, Grade 2, IDC, right, 2cm, 0/2 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'Others\' Experience', '', 'It\'s important to stay informed by researching, but it is just as important to have a positive outlook on a cancer free future.', 'Valerie Chen', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/841791', '', ''),
('Lymph vascular indeterminate', 'March 2016', 'Any positive stories of patients with indeterminate LVI?', '', 'Indeterminate LVI', 'Others\' Experience', 'Indeterminate LVI', 'If it\'s indeterminate it usually means small and focal (or not there). Extensive is the one that really counts.', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/841791', '', ''),
('Lymph vascular indeterminate', 'Mar 1, 2016', 'Asking for positive stories with indeterminate vascular lymph ', 'Lymph node removal: Sentinel, Mastectomy: Left & Right, Prophylatic mastectomy: Left ', 'Stage IIA, Grade 2, IDC, right, 2cm, 0/2 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'Others\' Experience', '', 'A patient with a similar situation recommends to enjoy every minute of your life because it is possible. It is important to keep reading and researching bc that is empowering as it allows patients to remember that a \"nice long cancer free life is in your power\"\".  If it is indeterinate', ' that usually means that it is small and focal', ' so they should expect to do well. \"', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/841791'),
('Tell me a (happy) bone island story :)', '', '', '', 'IDC, Stage IIA, Grade 2, 3/12 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2- ', 'Others\' experience', '', 'The patient had a bone island spotted on her CT after having a gallbladder surgery. She had to have it followed up and wants to know if there is anything serious about having a bone island. \nAccording to other patient experiences, having a bone island on a CT scan is not cancerous and is nothing to be worried about. PET and bone scans confirmed the same. Oncologists showed no signs of worry either. \n', 'Kriti Bhardwaj ', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/840980', '', ''),
('Worried about making decision......', '', '', '', 'Grade 2 Stage IIA BC, ER+ PR+ HER+', 'Others\' Experience', '', 'Potential risks of chemotherapy outweigh the benefits of low recurrence rate. Having a low oncotype score tells you that chemotherapy will likely be ineffective as it is a genetic assay test that looks at the specifics of the tumor. It is possible to undergo chemotherapy and not  reduce the already low risk at all. Instead,  chemotherapy can leave you with permanent side effects. Chemotherapy only targets fast growing cells and yours might not fit in that category depending upon your age and the oncotype score. Instead of chemotherapy, the patients are given Tamoxifen  and eventually, Zoladex shots to  suppress the ovaries.The oncotype score between 3 and 7% suggests that the recurrence risk is very low which is a good news. \n', 'Kriti Bhardwaj ', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/827354', '', ''),
('Worried about reoccurrence', '', '', '', 'Grade 3 Stage IIB BC, PR+ ER+ HER- Invasive Ductal Carcinoma. 2 rounds of chemotherapy followed by lumpectomy and radiation. ', 'Others\' Experience', '', 'Grade 3 is more aggressive than grade 2 or grade 1, but chemotheraphy is more effective in knocking grade 3 out, than say grade 1. It is common for people to have thoughts of reoccurance in the back of their mind, after they just finished chemo. There are lots of ways to lessen the worry and encoruage yourself, for example exercising or meditating. ', 'Dennis Luu ', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/865897', '', ''),
('Xeloda - hormone-positive + cancer post-neoadjuvant chemo', '', '', '', 'HR+, post dose-dense neoadjuvant chemotherapy/post surgery. Xelado taken being HR+?', 'Others\' Experience', '', 'Xeloda per oral typically for tiple negative breast cancer. Uncertain if Xeloda is responsive to HR+. Xeloda possibly hinders repsonsiveness to Tamoxafin/Al. Younger cancer patients with HR+ typically perscirbed Xelado. Possible new CDK4/6 inhibitor for ER/PR+. ', 'Harrison Klinski', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/870859', '', ''),
('Xeloda - hormone-positive + cancer post-neoadjuvant chemo', '', '', '', 'HR+, post surgery (Should Xeloda be taken?)', 'Others\' Experience', '', 'Xeloda is primarily for Triple negative breast cancer. It is unclear if it is effective for HR+. Some oncologists think it might interfere with HR therapy and don\'t prescribe it. But others do prescribe for young patients with HR+, node+ BC (after surgery).', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/870859', '', 'What does NCCN say?'),
('Xeloda - hormone-positive + cancer post-neoadjuvant chemo', '', '', '', 'Stage IIB, Grade 3, HR+, post surgery', 'Others\' Experience', '', 'Xeloda, oral chemotherapy, is used primarily for patients with triple negative breast cancer. The effect of xeloda on patients with HR+ is uncertain, but doesn\'t mean that it won\'t be beneficial. MO typically don\'t prescribe due to the fact that it may hinders the effects of HR therapy. Some younger patients do get prescribed xeloda, even though they are HR+, node+. ', 'Dennis Luu ', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/870859', '', ''),
('Xeloda - hormone-positive + cancer post-neoadjuvant chemo', 'July 5th 2018 ', '', '', 'Stage IIB, Grade 3, HR+, post surgery', 'Others\' Experience', '', 'Xeloda is usually given to patients with triple negative breast cancer. MO mentioned that hormone-receptor-positives do not benefit from Xeloda. One patient also took Xeloda simutanelously with Tamoxifen.', 'Amen Aiwekhoe ', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/870859', '', ''),
('Low WBC 1 year after stage 1 bc surgery and radiation', '', 'Patient is scared regarding a drop in her WBC score a year after surgery and radiation', '', ' [Post chemotherapy OR Post radiation]', 'Others\' Experience; ', 'Low WBC', 'Lower WBC counts can be seen for ~2 years after treatment, especially chemotherapy. WBC counts may increase though perhaps not to the same level as pre-treatment. Even with lower WBC counts, there does not seem to be a higher rate of unrelated infections. ', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/840902', '', 'Any data/publications to support that lower WBCs do not result in higher infections?'),
('Elevated Liver enzymes.', 'November 9th, 2014', '', '', 'Stage IIA, IDC, ER+/PR-, HER2+', 'Others\' Experience; Encouragement', '', 'There are other factors that can elevate your liver enzyme count. If you have just finished chemo it is unlikely that the elevated count coule be an indicator of metastatic disease but always double check. Other factors that can influence is the consumption of alcohol, Tylenol or pain medicine when mixed with anesthesia after surgery. Stay hydrated and hold different medicines and supplements as recommended by your doctor.', 'Sarah Taga', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/826109', '', ''),
('Elevated Liver enzymes.', 'November 2014', 'Patient is concerned regarding elevated liver enzymes and is asking if there is anything else that could cause this. ', '', 'Stage II, HR+', 'Others\' Experience; Encouragement', '', 'Non-cancer factors could elevate liver enzymes including pain medicine mixed with anesthesia after surgery. \n\nElevated liver enzymes not likely to be related to metastatic disease so soon after surgery/ chemo', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/826109', '', ''),
('Elevated Liver enzymes.', 'November 9th, 2014', '', '', 'Stage II Breast Cancer', 'Others\' Experience; Encouragement', '', 'Patient had 4 tumors at stage 2 and recieved her final chemo treatment and radiation in 2013. Recently she had bloodwork done which came with the results of having elevated AST and ALT levels which my be an indicaion of liver damage. This is worrysome to here, thinking that the cancer came back. She is currently asking others if they have similar experiences or for comforting words. ', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/826109', '', ''),
('Elevated Liver enzymes.', 'November 8th, 2014', '', '', 'Stage II Breast Cancer', 'Others\' Experience; Encouragement', '', 'Patients had 4 tumors, stage 2, clear nodes, double mastectomy. She did chemo. She found that the results of her bloodwork were alarming, with AST at 223 and ALT at 92. However, her bloodwork results were normal only three or four months ago.  ', 'Zihan Zheng', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/826109', '', ''),
('Herceptin', 'July 12th, 2015', 'Patient is having side effects from using Heceptin and is looking for possible solutions', 'Patient went through 6 cycles of taxotere, carboplatin and herceptin, and colonoscopy showed no signs of trouble in intestines.', 'Stage 2 Breast Cancer', 'Others\' Experience; Herceptin; Side Effects', '', 'Patient is on herceptin once every three weeks and has diarrhea and loss of appetite, and is embarrased to leave the home. One responder reccomended probiotics like Philips Colon Health and Floraster and staying hydrated.', 'Devansh Dwivedy', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/833341', '', ''),
('Herceptin', 'July 2015', '', '', 'Stage 2 HER2+ BC', 'Others\' Experience; Herceptin; Side Effects', '', 'TCH treatment can cause diarrhea and lack of appetite that may cause significant weigt loss. Symptoms can be mitigated by taking probiotics like Philips colon health and culturelle.', 'Preetham Ramesh', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/833341', '', ''),
('Herceptin', 'July 12th/ 2015', '', 'She went thourgh 6 cycles of taxotere, carboplatin, and herceptin. ', 'Stage 2 HER2+ Breast Cancer', 'Others\' Experience; Herceptin; Side Effects', '', 'Since going to just the herceptin, the patient experkienced diarrhea and loss of appetite. Responders sussgest that she take probiotics and stay hydrated.', '', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/833341', '', ''),
('Low WBC 1 year after stage 1 bc surgery and radiation', '', '', '', 'Low white blood cell count after surgery and radiation', 'Others\' Experience; WBC; Bone Marrow', '', 'The low WBC can be seen for up to two years after treatment. Some of the contributors include tomaxifen because it can cause an increase in bone pain. Although the main contributor seems to be chemotherapy. The patient is worried about bone marrow damage to the sternum, but looks like that should not be the major contributor to the low levels of white blood cells. Many patients who are experiencing the low levels of WBC do not seem to get sick often, which indicates that the lower levels of WBC should not greatly affect their day to day lives. The issue corrects itself after a couple of years and most doctors did not seem to worried about the lower counts.', 'Dhriti Bolangadi', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/840902', '', ''),
('Low WBC 1 year after stage 1 bc surgery and radiation', '', '', '', 'Low white blood cell count after surgery and radiation, and possible damage to the bone marrow', 'Others\' Experience; WBC; Bone Marrow', '', 'It is normal for WBC count to be low after radiation or Chemo therapy. Normally the bone marrow replaces lost stem cells on a daily basis. Sometimes there is Bone marrow failure after chemo. This is called bone marrow suppression. The rate of cellular reproduction has decreased.', 'Michelle Carter', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/840902', '', ''),
('Low WBC 1 year after stage 1 bc surgery and radiation', '', '', '', '', 'Others\' Experience; WBC; Bone Marrow', '', 'Generally, WBC drops during treatment and can take up to a few years to stabilize at a level that is higher than that during treatment but still lower than pre-treatment levels. ', 'Preetham Ramesh', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/840902', '', ''),
('Low WBC months after chemo. Do I need a bone marrow biopsy ?', 'September 20, 2014', 'The patient is unsure whether their low blood count is due to tamoxifen, which is considered a rare side effect or a late side effect of chemo and radiation. This is why they are asking if it is necessary to get a bone marrow biopsy since they\'d rather avoid recieve getting a false positive. ', 'The patient has had 4 months of chemo, 2 months of radiation and tamoxifen. Their WBC is around 2.1 (above3.7 is normal), neutrophil count is 0.9 (above 1.7 is normal), and red blood count is almost normal.  They have had a lymph node removal (left) as well as a masectomy (left)', 'IDC, Stage IIA, Grade 2, 1/28 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'Others\' Experience; WBC; Bone Marrow', '', 'It is said that it takes time for counts to get back to normal after medication and chemo. A previous patient was not recommended a bonde marrow biopsy. One patient recommends doing a bone marorw biopsy since its better to recieve a false positive than a false negative. ', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/824728', '', ''),
('Low WBC months after chemo. Do I need a bone marrow biopsy ?', 'Setember 2014', 'Should a patient bother with a bone marrow biopsy if they have irregularly low blood count post-chemo?', 'IDC, 1cm, Stage IIA, Grade 2, 1/28 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'Stage II Breast Cancer, post-chemo', 'Others\' Experience; WBC; Bone Marrow', '', 'While doctors inform that it takes time for blood counts to restore to pre-treatment levels after chemo, patients suggest undergoing a bone marrow biopsy anyway to ensure that their blood levels are not preparing to crash, etc, and for peace of mind.', 'Kendall Vanderwouw', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/824728', '', ''),
('All Done!!!', '', '', '', 'Stage IIA Grade 2', 'Positive Affirmations', '', 'Patient has had a Lupectomy on the right side and is gone chemotheraphy, radiation and hormonal therapies in the past. Five and a half years later the patient is considered low risk and is off AI soon. ', 'Hamza Hussain ', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/821352', '', ''),
('All Done!!!', 'May 2014', 'I just completed 5 years of hormone therapy. Feeling excited.', '', 'Stage II BC', 'Positive Affirmations', '', 'Post-completion of 5 year hormone therapy, next followup is 1 year. ', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/821352', '', ''),
('All Done!!!', '', '', '', 'Stage IIA', 'Positive Affirmations', '', 'After a lumpectomy, chemotherapy (Adriamycin), Radiation, and hormonal therapy (Femara) over a 5.5 year period, patient deemed low risk. Doesn\'t have to come back for another MRI until a the next fall (16 months)', '', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/821352', '', ''),
('An anniversary--7 years', 'October 2015', '', '', 'ILC StageIIA Grade 2 ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'Positive Affirmations', '', 'Patient advised that when you feel down or feel like your falling into darkness remember the quote \"So far you have survived 100% of your worst days. You are doing great.\"\" Made adivsing patient feel better that when listing her worst days she could only get to 35', ' helps to see how many good days you have had\"', 'Daniel Chen', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/836222', ''),
('An anniversary--7 years', '', '', '', 'Stage IIA Grade 2', 'Positive Affirmations', '', '\"Glad that you are well and able to keep stress in perspective\"\"\"', 'Hamza Hussain', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/836222', '', ''),
('An anniversary--7 years', 'October 2015', 'No query', '', 'Stage II BC, HR+, post-treatment', 'Positive Affirmations', '', 'No insights? How about advice? \"So far you have survived 100% of your worst days. You are doing great.\"\"\"', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/836222', '', ''),
('An anniversary--7 years', 'October 2015', '', '', 'Stage IIA, Grade 2, 0/1 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'Positive Affirmations', '', 'The patient had a Lumpectomy on her right side and it was 7 years since her diagnosis. Her personal life has made her reflect on what she calls her \"worst days: and she came up with only 35 throughout her life. The day she was diagnosed with cancer was up there. She reflected on how it felt to be diagnosed which she describes as being \"\"pushed off a very tall building and was just falling into darkness.\"\" \"', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/836222', '', ''),
('Good day', 'May 5, 2014', 'Patient is sharing her tough experience with cancer and is finally feeling that there is a light at the end of the tunnel', '', 'Stage IIA, DC, 1cm, Grade 3, 1/9 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'Positive Affirmations', '', 'The patient was rediagonsed for BC, July 2013 after first DCIS in 2007. Patient worked through 1st half of chemotherapy and returned home for the 2nd half. Patient felt very depressed and scared during the process of chemotherapy. Patient was able to return back to work, they usually wore a wig to help with hairloss but got tired of it and decided to no longer wear the wig. The patient gained a lot of confidence and felt that once the wig was removed they were able to feel like they were \"moving on\"\"\"', 'Amen Aiwekhoe ', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/820809', '', ''),
('Good day', 'May 5th, 2014', '', '', 'Stage 2 Breast Cancer', 'Positive Affirmations', '', 'Patients and responders are talking about how they feel truy recovered and strong again once they have their hair growing again and their energy back after chemo. It makes them feel lik9e they are truly getting better and getting close to a \"new normal\"\" as one describes it.\"', 'Devansh Dwivedy', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/820809', '', ''),
('Good day', 'May 5, 2014', '', '', 'Stage IIA, DC, 1cm, Grade 3, 1/9 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'Positive Affirmations', '', '', 'Harrison Klinski', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/820809', '', ''),
('5 Years ago', '', '', '', 'Stage IIA Breast cancer ', 'Positive Affirmations ', '', '5 years post cancer, had Lumpectomy surgery on halloween after receiving diagnosis, doctor had said it looked bad but it is early and very treatable. Started Chemo right after the new year, and with 6 months left of treatment her hair is still the same as was and she is feeling much better than when she had started.', 'Jaspreet Deol', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/813700', '', ''),
('5 Years ago', '', '', '', 'Stage IIA', 'Positive Affirmations ', '', '5 years post cancer diagnosis, NCCN guidelines recommend a physical exam once every year starting the sixth year after cancer treatment', 'Katherine Brizuela', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/813700', '', ''),
('5 Years ago', '', 'Its my 5 year anniversary of diagnosis. And I feel great. Happy Anniversary to me?\n\nOR\n\nIs anyone having a 5 year anniversary of diagnosis?', '', 'Stage IIA', 'Positive Affirmations ', '', 'Physical exam is recommended annually after completion of 5 year treatment', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/813700', '', 'Celebration of 5 year mileston'),
('6 years!!', '', '', '', 'Stage II BC', 'Positive Affirmations ', '', 'Doctor had diagnosed with Stage II 6 years ago. Has been cancer free since then. Many other patients are seeing this news to be inspiring. Patient acknowledged doctor\'s kind words of encouragement as a form of hope to get through tougher days. ', 'Dhriti Bolangadi', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/825847', '', ''),
('6 years!!', '', '', '', 'Stage IIA Grade 2', 'Positive Affirmations ', '', 'No insights, just be happy, enjoy life and never give up hope.', 'Sarah Taga', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/825847', '', ''),
('6 years!!', '', 'No query', '', 'Stage II BC', 'Positive Affirmations ', '', 'No insights', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/825847', '', ''),
('And now for some good news', 'Feburary 2015', '', '', 'ILC Stage IIA Grade 2 ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'Positive Affirmations/ Side Effects', '', 'Lung nodules may not be indicator of breast cancer metastasis to the lung, check levels of vitamin D, calcium, and ACE as the elevation of these along with lung nodules may be more indicative of sarcoidosis', 'Daniel Chen', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/828923', '', ''),
('And now for some good news', '', '', '', 'Stage IIA Breast Cancer', 'Positive Affirmations/ Side Effects', '', 'Patient has said that the phsycian cannot find the nodule anymore. ', 'Jaspreet Deol', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/828923', '', ''),
('And now for some good news', '', '', '', 'Stage II Breast Cancer ', 'Positive Affirmations/ Side Effects', '', 'Check vitamin D/calcium/ACE levels - can be signs of sarcoidosis ', 'Kelvin Du ', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/828923', '', ''),
('And now for some good news', 'Feburary 2015', 'No query', '', 'Stage II BC, 5 years post-treatment, has lung nodule', 'Positive Affirmations/ Side Effects', '', 'In case of lung nodules, check vitamin D/calcium/ACE levels - can be signs of sarcoidosis ', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/828923', '', ''),
('2 Years Ago Today', 'December 26th, 2014', 'Anyone else still get anxious every time before annual diagnostic mammogram?', '', 'Stage IIA', 'recurrence ', '', 'getting anxious before mamogram screening.', 'Duyen Nguyen', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/827201', '', ''),
('2 Years Ago Today', '', '', '', 'Stage IIA, Grade 2, 1/3 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'recurrence ', '', '2 years post cancer diagnosis, worried about recurrence and anxious/worried about upcomming mamogram appointment. Take Xanax?', 'Harrison Klinski', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/827201', '', ''),
('2 Years Ago Today', '', '', '', 'Stage IIA, Grade 2, 1/3 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'recurrence ', '', '2 years post cancer diagnosis, worried about recurrence and anxious/worried about upcomming mamogram appointment. Take Xanax?', 'Harrison Klinski', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/827201', '', ''),
('2 Years Ago Today', 'December 2014', 'Anyone else still get anxious every time before annual diagnostic mammogram?', '', 'Stage II, HR+, on maintenance hormone therapy', 'recurrence ', '', 'Anxiety before screening mammogram post-treatment is normal. Perhaps take XanaX?', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/827201', '', ''),
('Chemo over, no scans or MRI - just wait for something to happen?', 'July 2015', '', '', 'Stage II BC ', 'recurrence Concerns; No Scans', '', 'The patient is done with 6 rounds of chemo but will continue with Herceptin, a bi-lateral masectomy since they are BRCA2+ and a hysterectomy. The patient is left feeling uneasy since they were told that no scans are needed and to report if something \"does not feel right.\"\" Many patients have experienced this and are left feeling the same way. Some have said that they did not feel symptoms or pain until it was too late. Some also are left wondering if their pain is worth reporting to their doctors.\"', 'Stacy Rivera ', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/840723', '', ''),
('Chemo over, no scans or MRI - just wait for something to happen?', 'January 26th, 2016', '', '', 'Stage II Breast Cancer', 'recurrence Concerns; No Scans', '', 'The patient is done with 6 rounds of chemo but will continue with Herceptin since she is HER2+. She did not have lymph node involvement but a bilateral mastectomy was called for because she was BRCA2+. The patient was told that no scans were needed and she needed to \"listen to her body\"\" to report anything wrong. She feels uncomfortable with this wait and see approach', ' worrying that she would have missed the best period for treatment when the disease comes back at the level that she can feel it. Rather', ' she prefers to proactively take the scans and start treatment at an early stage', ' if necessary.\"', 'Zihan Zheng'),
('Chemo over, no scans or MRI - just wait for something to happen?', 'January 2016', 'Does it make sense to not get any scans post-treatment unless there are symptoms?', '', 'Post-treatment stage II', 'Recurrence queries', '', 'Scans are not recommended in the absence of symptoms, partly to limit exposure to radiation and partly for cost. \n\nBe vigilant about any unusual symptoms and be proactive about asking for scans if something seems off', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/840723', '', ''),
('Worried about reoccurrence', '', '', '', 'Diagnosed with stage 2 breast cancer. Finished 2 rounds of chemotherapy followed with lumpectomy and radiation. Worried about reoccurrence of breast cancer because they have Grade 3 cancer cells.', 'recurrence Queries', '', 'Grade 3 cancer cells are the most invasive and fast growing cells, but cheotherapy works well to eradicate the growth. Patient sees more posts relating to Grade 2 and 3 cancer cells and wants to know the prognosis of the different grades. The results with chemotherapy for this patient looks good at the moment because of the 90% reduction in tumor size and eradication of cancer in lymph node. Patient is worried about the recurrence of cancer in other areas of the body. There is a chance of reocurrence because the grade of the cells is higher, but the aggressive chemotherapy method could prevent occurence of cancer elsewhere.', 'Dhriti Bolangadi', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/865897', '', ''),
('Worried about reoccurrence', '', '', '', 'Grade 3 Stage IIB BC', 'recurrence Queries', '', 'Grade 3 is more aggressive than grade 2 but can might be better in that chemo can be very effective knocking it out. ', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/865897', '', 'Followup: Is this actually true? What do the NCCN guidelines say about this?\"\"'),
('Best oncologist in minnesota', 'March 2016', 'Patient is looking for suggestions regarding oncologist in Minnesota', '', '-', 'Referral', '', 'No insights', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/842548', '', ''),
('Abraxine', '', '', '', 'Stage II Breast Cancer', 'Right Treatment?', '', 'Abraxine has fewer side effects when compared to taxol. You might loose some hair and will be fatigued over time. Taste buds change and nails get a bit grundgy. After the run time is finished the side effects are reversed. ', 'Hamza Hussain', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/840173', '', ''),
('Abraxine', '', '', '', 'Stage II Breast Cancer', 'Right Treatment?', '', 'Patient has had Lumpectomy and a lymph node removal, the physician is reccommending the switch to Abraxine instead of the continuation of Taxol, and patient is curious to know whether there are side affects and the affectiveness on the tumor.', 'Jaspreet Deol', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/840173', '', ''),
('Abraxine', 'Jan \'16', '', '', 'Stage 2 BC undergoing AC ', 'Right Treatment?', '', 'Abraxine is taxol but designed to have less side effects.    ', 'Preetham Ramesh', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/840173', '', ''),
('Almost 4 years breast cancer free and doctor won\'t do any tests', 'July 2014', 'I am on maintenance hormone therapy and am hoping to get scans to monitor disease progression but my doctor won\'t give it. Any thoughts?', '', 'Stage II, post treatment', 'Right treatment?', '', 'Scans are generally not recommended by NCCN post-treatment except in the case of symptoms. The idea is to minimize radiation exposure. ', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/822537', '', ''),
('Chemo regimen for Stage 2 A, no lymph nodes', '', '', '', 'Stage II, no-node TNBC', 'Right treatment?', '', 'Aggressive TNBC requires aggressive chemotherapy 6 cycles of AC every 3 weeks (HOW TO DEFINE)?', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/859565', '', ''),
('Chemo regimen for Stage 2 A, no lymph nodes', '', '', '', '', 'Right treatment?', '', 'Since a triple negative is agressive, it is treated with many rounds of chemotherphy which is normal in the casr of this is patient. ', 'Hamza Hussain', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/859565', '', ''),
('Chemo regimen for Stage 2 A, no lymph nodes', 'October \'17', '', '', 'Grade 3 IDC; triple negative', 'Right treatment?', '', 'Triple negative means that the cancer is very aggressive and is usually treated with many rounds of chemotherapy.', 'Preetham Ramesh', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/859565', '', ''),
('Looking for Advice', 'Feb 2019', 'Patient is getting 0 communication from her physcian and does not know what treatment to take on', '', 'Stage II breast cancer ', 'Right Treatment?', '', 'Since aggressive treatment is a priority, a full mastectomy is highly effective for preventing cancer reappearing later down the line.  Test results play a huge role in determining the treatment that best suits your diagnosis.  Exploring the option of EndoPredict test could be helpful; its used to predict the risk of distant recurrence of early-stage, hormone-receptor-positive, HER2-negative breast cancer that is either node-negative or has up to three positive lymph nodes.  There has also been good insight from Oncotype DX Tests.  Among other things, this test helps determine womans risk of early-stage, estrogen-receptor-positive breast cancer recurrence and the likelyhood of benefit from chemotherapy.  It also assesses the risk of DCIS recurrence, risk of other invasive cancer development and likelihood of benefit from radiation therapy. ', 'Chiara Marley', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/870003', '', 'Appropriate use of Oncotype DX'),
('Lymph vascular invasion?', '', 'Should I get chemotherapy (recommended by oncologist) and lymph node dissection (recommended by surgeon)? I have LVI and SNB 1 node positive and am young (41).', '', 'Young, LVI, SNB-positive', 'Right Treatment?', '[Chemotherapy OR NOT] [ALND OR NOT]', 'Most patients like her got standard chemotherapy ACT\n\nSome recommended second opinion; Mammaprint/ Oncotype testing\n\nSome concerned with lymph node dissection because of risk of lymphedema\n\nBased on NCCN guidelines, this patient should not get LND', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/852274', '', ''),
('What treatment is Best for stage 2b?', '', '', '', 'BC stage IIB, ER+/PR+, HER2- , mastectomy performed on right breast, 9/12 positive lymphnodes,  ', 'Right Treatment? ', '', 'Chemotherapy is the best option because of lymph node involvement as all the remaining cancer cells need be removed. \nBeing  surrounded by supportive people and doctors makes it a lot more easier to go through the treatment.  \n        \n', 'Kriti Bhardwaj ', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/856520', '', ''),
('Abraxine', 'January 2016', 'My doctor just told me he wants to start me on Abraxine instead of taxol. I was wondering what side effects anyone has had?\n \nAND \n\nDid it help shrink the tumor?', '', 'Stage II taking Abraxane', 'Right Treatment? \n\nAND \n\nOthers\' experience', '', 'Abraxane is taxol with fewer side effects\n\nSome side effects include changes in taste buds and nails getting grundgy but the are reversible', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/840173', '', ''),
('Do I need chemo?', 'May 20th, 2018', '', '', 'IDC Stage 1', 'Right Treatment?; Chemotherapy', '', 'Age is a big factor in the agression of your treatment with younger patients getting more agressive treatment. An Oncotype DX test would help in this decision to determine if the chemo would be beneficial, this test is a genomic test that shows how cancer would likely behave and respond to treatment. ', 'Sarah Taga', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/864726', '', ''),
('Do I need chemo?', 'May 2018', 'Patient is asking if getting chemotherapy is a good idea if the mammaprint result is low. ', '', 'Low grade, HR+', 'Right Treatment?; Chemotherapy', '', 'From new guidelines (NEEDS CONFIRMATION), micromets in sentinel node are not considered node+.\n\nFor low grade HR+ breast cancer, Oncotype testing will help inform decision about whether to take chemotherapy', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/864726', '', ''),
('Do I need chemo?', 'May 20th, 2018', '', '', 'Stage II BC, IDC', 'Right Treatment?; Chemotherapy', '', 'Pateint recommends that she do her own research and ask her doctor specific questions about her situation and how the decision should depend on factors such as age. It is being recommended to ask for an Oncotype or a Mammaprint before making the final decision. ', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/864726', '', ''),
('Do I need chemo?', 'May 20th, 2018', '', '', 'Stage II Breast Cancer', 'Right Treatment?; Chemotherapy', '', 'The patient has a few positive nodes and a low likelihood of recurrence. She belives that the patient has 100% agency to make the chemo decision. She suggests that patient should do her own research and get second opinion.', 'Zihan Zheng', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/864726', '', ''),
('Lymph vascular invasion?', '', 'Patient is concerned about going through chemotherapy and is asking if she should get a second opinion', '', '', 'Right Treatment?; Chemotherapy', '', '', '', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/852274', '', ''),
('Am I crazy?', 'October 2015', '', '', 'IDC Stage IIB Grade1 ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'Right Treatment?; Chemotherapy; Oncology Score', '', 'With an oncoscore of 9 you have a very low possibility of occurence as such chemo\'s benefit is unlikely to outweigh its negative side effects, hormonal therapy would be th emore reccommnended route, that being said if you are set on chem and understand what you would like to get from it and what you will get from it most people do not regret the decesion.', 'Daniel Chen', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/835563', '', ''),
('Am I crazy?', '', '', '', 'Stage IIB Grade 1', 'Right Treatment?; Chemotherapy; Oncology Score', '', 'Patient has an onco score of 9 and is considering undergoing chemotherapy. She has one positive node which is why she is considering but she hears many patients decide against chemotherapy even with a positive node. She is wondering what she is missing. One person reccomended she look into hormone therapy while the rest of the responses were split between for chemo and against.', 'Karen Boctor', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/835563', '', ''),
('Am I crazy?', '', '', '', 'Stage II Breast Cancer', 'Right Treatment?; Chemotherapy; Oncology Score', '', 'hormone therapy is an alternative. one patient was recommended to have chemo at least once as insurance. It\'s all depend on what the onc. thinks and what the patient feels the best for them. There is no good or bad.', 'Linh Nguyen', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/835563', '', ''),
('Am I crazy?', 'October 2015', 'Patient is inquiring if doing chemotherapy with an onco score of 9 is a good idea as women with no positive nodes also do chemo.', '', 'IDC stage II, one node positive, low Oncotype (9), HR+', 'Right Treatment?; Chemotherapy; Oncology Score', '', 'Benefit from chemo under these circumstances is 3-5%. Considerations include age (younger women want to treat cancer aggressively with chemo), Oncotype score (patients with >20/25 often go with checmo). For HR+, hormone therapy might be better than chemo', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/835563', '', ''),
('ER- PR weakly positive Her2 -', 'June 5th, 2015', '', '', 'Stage II Breast Cancer', 'Right Treatment?; Targeted Hormonal Therapy', '', 'The patient has a cancer diagnosis that is weakly positive on PR and not a true triple negative. Husband is deliberating whether her cancer warrants targeted hormonal therapy. Percentage of progesterone receptors can help determine whether to get targeted hormonal therapy but sometimes people do it regardless of how high the percentage is. ', 'Jo Kuramkote', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/832362', '', ''),
('ER- PR weakly positive Her2 -', 'June 2015', 'Patient is asking if she can receive hormonal therapy without being a \"true\"\" triple negative. \"', '', 'Stage II, weakly PR+', 'Right Treatment?; Targeted Hormonal Therapy', '', 'Hormone therapy can be given to patients with weak HR+ (even as low as 1% or 5% staining) though it depends on the oncologist', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/832362', '', 'CHECK GUIDELINES'),
('ER- PR weakly positive Her2 -', 'June 5th, 2015', '', '', 'Stage II Breast Cancer', 'Right Treatment?; Targeted Hormonal Therapy', '', 'The patient\'s wife is weakly positive on PR  and negative on the other two areas. He is wondering if her wife could recenve targeted/ hormonal therapy even if she is not triple negative. Another patient suggested that her wife check her percentage of progesterone receptors from the pathology and ask for a second opinion if not receiving hormone targeted therapy did not sit well with her wife.', 'Zihan Zheng', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/832362', '', ''),
('8 years ago', '', '', '', 'Stage IIA Grade 2 BC', 'Side Effects', '', 'Patient was diagnosed 8 years ago and had surgery, chemotherapy, radiation therapy and hormonal therapy. Other patients are asking about the issues that femara (a hormonal treatment) caused within the patient. The patient came off of the hormonal therapy 5 years after diagnosis, but still has some effects. The effects involve vaginal atropy and a \"fuzzy\"\" feeling regarding memory.\"', 'Dhriti Bolangadi', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/849413', '', ''),
('8 years ago', '', '', '', 'Stage IIA Grade 2 BC', 'Side Effects', '', 'Diagnosed approximately in 2008 and undergoing chemo in 2008 along, radiation therapy, and had a lumpectomy on the right breast. Patient has said she was very happy and healthy through the support she had received from everyone.', 'Jaspreet Deol', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/849413', '', ''),
('Any help?', '', '', '', 'No patient insights', 'Side Effects', '', 'Current AC treatment leaving symptoms of constipation, and hindered motor skills/gate. Other alternatives to colace/Senna for constipatin relief? Miralax/Senocot/Magnesium 007 for constipation relief?', 'Harrison Klinski', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/868762', '', ''),
('Any help?', '', '', '', 'No patient insights', 'Side Effects', '', 'Side effects of AC treatment include nausea, slow motor skills and difficulty concentrating. Anti-nausea medications cause constipation. Several alternative methods for dealing with constipation include Miralax, ducolax, Senocot, magnesium supplements and pitted dates. ', 'Jo Kuramkote', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/868762', '', ''),
('Any help?', '', '', '', 'Stage Two Breast Cancer after one round of AC ', 'Side Effects', '', 'After an initial AC round, patients complain of constipation from anti-nausea medication. Many patients believe that Miralax and Ducolax minimize constipation, and are a reasonable option readily available without perscription, and that Senocot is effective (with a perscription). Constipation is also minimized by eating pitted prunes, drinking water, and taking Magnesium. Patients caution to be wary around heat because of altered gait and induced nausea from the treatment. While Phenargan and Zephran make patients mentally uncomfortable (with loopiness/headaches), peppermint oil can relieve nausea and help calm nerves.', 'Kendall Vanderwouw', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/868762', '', ''),
('Any help?', '', '', '', 'Stage 2 BC undergoing AC', 'Side Effects', '', 'Constipation from AC can be alleviated by taking miralax, metamucil, and dulcolax. More natural remedies like drinking water and eating prunes can help as well. Nausea and headaches can be alleviated by smelling peppermint essential oil.  ', 'Preetham Ramesh ', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/868762', '', ''),
('Any help?', '', 'Patient is inquiring regarding constipation solutions during her treatement', '', 'Stage 2 BC taking AC or TCHP', 'Side Effects', '', 'Constipation from anti-nausea medication when on AC chemotherapy can be alleviated with Miralax, Ducolox, Senocot, Magnesium, Colace, Metamucil, pitted prunes and lots of water. Combination of such medicines can even be started *before* each chemotherapy round.  \n\nAnti-nausea meds, Phenagran and Zephran, could cause loopiness/headaches\n\nPeppermint essential oil could be used for headaches/ nausea\n\nAbnormal gait and difficulty concentrating are side effects of AC and THCP regimens. So be cautious\n\nSome chemo? (AC, 5-FU, Methotrexate, paclitaxel) can cause less sensitivity to heat and result in burns. \n\n', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/868762', '', 'Which chemo causes reduced heat sensitivity?'),
('Any help?', 'December 2018', '', '', 'No patient insights', 'Side Effects', '', 'After the patient has completed one round of AC, they are experiencing nausea so they are taking medication. They are also experiencing constipation and delayed motor skills. Others have experienced slowed motor skills and suggested to take things slowly. For constipation, many were prescribed Miralax, magnesium supplements, and ducolax. ', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/868762', '', ''),
('Bone Pain with Tamoxifen Use?', 'January 2015', '', '', 'Stage 2A IDC', 'Side Effects', '', 'Tamoxifen can cause soreness to different parts of the body but not sure if this is the cause of the pain or if it is a combination of other medication. Taking glucosamine and chrondroitin could provide temporary relief. ', 'Deepthi Mohanraj', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/828017', '', ''),
('Bone Pain with Tamoxifen Use?', '', '', '', 'Stage 2A IDC', 'Side Effects', '', 'Tamoxifen linked to joint and bone aches but no concrete evidence. Aches may be due to other cancer symptoms', 'Jo Kuramkote', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/828017', '', ''),
('Bone Pain with Tamoxifen Use?', 'January 2015', 'Patient is asking if bone pain is normal when using Tamoxifen along with other side effects', '', 'Stage II, HR+, HER2+ ', 'Side Effects', '', 'Tamoxifen could result in pain in various parts of the body - spine, lower back, hip, leg, bone (SHOULD CHECK)\n\nLymphedema could result in Soreness and tenderness under the treated breast even without swelling (Check cording)', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/828017', '', ''),
('Bone Pain with Tamoxifen Use?', '', '', '', '', 'Side Effects', '', '', 'Snow Wu', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/828017', '', ''),
('Breast Cancer - you\'re kidding me!', 'May 2015', 'Patient is inquiring about various side effects she is experiencing after her procedure targetting Stage 2 breast Cancer', '', 'Stage II BC', 'Side Effects', '', 'Try Advil for joint inflammation and pain associated with hormone blockers\n\nAlso its ok to take a break from surgeries for a while and revisit later. ', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/832185', '', ''),
('Stage 2A', '', '', '', 'Stage 2A Breast Cancer', 'Side Effects', '', 'Patient on 3rd round of Chemotherapy. Chemotherapy in the breast is usually given by drugs that will target cancer cell, with the use of injection in the veins or as pill. There are more side effects as chemotheray progresses. Patient is having soreness in kidney (left one specifically). My findings recommend that drinking water  and juices such as cranberry are helpful when experiencing soreness in the kidney.', 'Daniel Navarro', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/869991', '', ''),
('Stage 2A', '', '', '', 'Diagnosed with stage 2a Breast Cancer, has undergone 3rd round of chemotherapy', 'Side Effects', '', 'Patient feels soreness around her left kidney, has been advised to drink water and cranberry juice. At night, she sleeps in 1 hour increments, feels perpetually jet-lagged.', 'Sharan K. G.', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/869991', '', ''),
('Stage 2A', '', '', '', 'Stage 2 BC undergoing chemo', 'Side Effects', '', 'Drink water and cranberry juice for kidney-related soreness?', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/869991', '', ''),
('TCHP Side Effects', 'Began December 2018', '', '', 'Stage Two Breast Cancer, doing TCHP', 'Side Effects', '', 'Side effects of THCP treatment primarily effected patients on days 4- 5, although many patients cited days 2-10 as uncomfortable. Some patients believe that getting injections on Tuesdays or Wednesdays maximized the amount of time they spent at work, and delayed their discomfort until weekends.', 'Kendall Vanderwouw', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/868702', '', ''),
('TCHP Side Effects', '', '', '', 'Stage 2B Breast Cancer', 'Side Effects', '', 'TCHP side effects lasted about a week after treatment but seems to peak around day 3-4 for patients. ', 'Preetham Ramesh', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/868702', '', ''),
('TCHP Side Effects', 'December 2018', '', '', 'Stage 2 Breast Cancer, Patients doing TCHP Rx', 'Side Effects', '', 'The side effects of TCHP have varying time frames, a majority of which fell in between 2-10 days, a few of the patients emphasized a peak in side effects in days 3-5', 'Sagel Ejantkar', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/868702', '', ''),
('TCHP Side Effects', '', '', '', 'Stage 2 BC; Patients doing TCHP Rx', 'Side Effects', '', 'TCHP side effects could be bad between days 2-10 but peaked days 3-5', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/868702', '', ''),
('TCHP Side Effects', 'Octoer 1 2018 ', '', '', 'Stage 2 BC; Patients doing TCHP Rx', 'Side Effects', '', 'Patients usually recieve side effects from TCHP 2-10 days. side effects could also wear off 2-3 days ', 'Amen Aiwekhoe ', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/868702', '', ''),
('Calcium levels while on Anastrozole', 'October 2017', '', '', 'Stage 2A IDC', 'Side Effects; Anastrozole; Calcium Levels', '', 'Calcium levels often fluctuate and its important to not be dehydrated on the day of the test. Normal range is between 9-10.', 'Deepthi Mohanraj', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/859153', '', ''),
('Calcium levels while on Anastrozole', 'October 17', '', '', 'Stage 2A IDC', 'Side Effects; Anastrozole; Calcium Levels', '', 'Blood calcium levels in the can vary. For healthy adults, the healthy range is anywhere in the 9\'s. It\'s important to not drink too much water before gettig tested as this can dilute calcium in the blood, among other things.  ', 'Preetham Ramesh ', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/859153', '', ''),
('Calcium levels while on Anastrozole', 'October 2017', 'Patient is asking if anyone has experienced a change in calcium levels while on Anastrozole', '', 'Stage 2', 'Side Effects; Anastrozole; Calcium Levels', '', 'Treatment for breast cancer should not impact normal blood calcium levels. \n\nLetrozole/ Anastrozole might result in trigger finger, thumb, ankle though these symptoms may vary by brand.', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/859153', '', ''),
('Is arm pain common?', 'January, 2015', '', '', 'Stage II BC', 'Side Effects; Arm Pain', '', 'Although this is said to not be a common symptom for BC, other patients have had the same symptom. The arm pain went away after treatments of Taxol.', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/827745', '', ''),
('Is arm pain common?', 'June 16th/ 2015', '', '', 'Stage 1 BC', 'Side Effects; Arm Pain', '', 'Some patients experience athritic-like arm pain before the diagnosis and  mastectomy. Some suspect that the arm pain is related to their breast cancer.', 'Zihan Zheng', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/827745', '', ''),
('Is arm pain common?', 'January 21st, 2015', 'Patient is asking if arm pain on the same side as the diagnosis is common in non-metastatic breast cancer patients.', '', 'Stage 2 BC', 'Side Effects; Arm Pain', '', 'Patients have reported the same pain but this pain has been resolved after several treatments of Taxol. ', 'Hamza Hussain', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/827745', '', ''),
('chemo treatment affecting asthma', 'January 2018', 'Can AC trigger asthma?', '', 'Stage II, taking AC or Taxor/ Taxotere, Herceptin', 'Side Effects; Asthma; Chemotherapy Side Effects', '', 'Asthma or respiratory problems can be seen with AC and Taxol/ Taxotere and Herceptin. Some patients have developed paroxysmal dyspnea and spasmodic coughing after chemo. Antibiotics and steroids can be given the first day of chemo, continuing for 5 days; while using a regular medication inhaler. After chemo treatment, the respiratory symptoms usually subside.', 'Smruti Vidwans, Katherine Brizuela, Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/861439', '', ''),
('Hair loss', 'June 2016', 'Patient is worried about hair loss and concerned as to how she can go about feeling better after chemotherapy', '', 'Stage II BC', 'Side Effects; Hair Loss', '', 'Patient is self concious and worried about hair loss. They are advised to get wigs, dress up, and take care of themselves in other ways to cope. ', 'Deepthi Mohanraj', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/844806', '', ''),
('Hair loss', 'March 14, 2017', '', '', 'Stage II BC ', 'Side Effects; Hair Loss', '', 'Difficulty emotionally coping with hairloss. Reference to \"Look Good', ' Feel Better\"\" by American Cancer Society. Use of a wig.\"', 'Harrison Klinski', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/844806', 'Very little patient insight'),
('Hair loss', 'June 2, 2016', '', '', 'Stage II BC ', 'Side Effects; Hair Loss', '', 'The patient is having a hard time dealing with hair loss after their second round of AC chemo. A patient said wearing wigs and keeping up with ones appearance by dressing up and wearing makeup can help with self esteem. Keeping busy can also help, not allowing the patient too much time to think about the hair loss. ', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/844806', '', ''),
('Hand & Foot syndrome', 'July 2016', 'Patient is experiencing side effects in her hands and feet and is asking for solutions for these', '', 'Stage II BC, Hand and Foot Syndrome', 'Side Effects; Hand and Feet', '', 'Current Taxotera treatment. Hand and Foot Syndrome causing itching/swelling. Oral Benadryl and Benadryl cream to stop incesint symptoms. \"Udderly Smooth Cream\"\" brand', ' applied 203 times/day possibly aleviate symptoms.\"', 'Harrison Klinski', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/847850', ''),
('Hand & Foot syndrome', '', '', '', 'Stage II BC', 'Side Effects; Hand and Feet', '', 'Patient is taking Taxotera and has hand and foot syndrome. Symptoms can be alleviated with oral benadryl and lotions with urea in them. ', 'Preetham Ramesh', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/847850', '', ''),
('Hand & Foot syndrome', 'September 8, 2016', '', '', 'Stage II BC', 'Side Effects; Hand and Feet', '', 'The patient is half way through their 12 weeks of taxotera that they recieve every 3 weeks. They are experiencing red itching hands, swollen feet that burn and are peeling which are forming calluses. They were recommended by their doctor to continue to take oral benadry and the cream which are not working. A patient recommended the \"utdderly smooth\"\" cream for their hands and feet and said to limit the pressure placed on feet.\"', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/847850', '', ''),
('Headaches', 'March 2018', 'The patient is experiencing nausea associated with severe headaches and is asking for solutions for these', '', 'Stage II, side effects of Zofran', 'Side Effects; Headaches', 'side effects management ', 'The cause of the headaches might be from the medication, Zofran, which suppresses nausea and vomiting. The body may need to adjust to the medications given to the new patient. The FDA has also approved Rolapitant to prevent chemotherapy-induced nausea and vomiting. Imitrex worked well for the patient to alleviate the headches', 'Katherine Brizuela, Zihan Zheng', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/863529', '', ''),
('Heart Damage After Chemo', 'February 8th, 2019', 'Patient has been told by her physician that she heart damage due to drugs and is looking for encouragement during this difficult time', 'The patient experienced shortness of breath one year ago. Her pulmonary test came back clear. Now she was told that her might have a heart damage caused by the chemo drugs.The heart harness test came back clear but she could not finish the cardiac treadmill stress test.', 'Stage 2 BC', 'Side Effects; Heart Damage; Encouragement ', '', 'Chemotherapy (adriamycin in particular) could lead to heart problems such ascardiomyopathy. Early symptoms of heart damage include shortness of breath and rising heart rate. This condition has escaped harness tests, but is often expressed with treadmill tests. Talk to your doctor and /or cardio-oncologist.', 'Smruti Vidwans, Zihan Zheng, Kendall Vanderwouw', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/869755', '', ''),
('Anyone currently on TCHP?', 'May 2015', 'Patient is looking for similar patients and asking about side effects shes experiencing and others have experienced with similar diagnosis', '', 'Stage II BC taking TCHP', 'Side Effects; Inter-Personal Patient Connections', '', 'Steroids  taken with AC can cause shortness of breath\n\nTCHP treatment can lead to various side effects including shortness of breath, diarrhea, and sharp pains', 'Smruti Vidwans, Stacy Rivera, Sagel Ejantkar', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/831321', '', ''),
('Leg & arm pain', 'April 2017', 'Are shin and lowering arm pain symptoms to be concerned about following treatment? Should someone experiencing these symptoms contact an oncologist?', 'Post-lumpectomy, (no other information given)', 'Stage II BC', 'Side Effects; Leg Pain; Arm Pain', '', 'Since the pain is in the arms and legs it could be due to an new exercise regimen. It is recommend you inform your doctor of any new pain post-treatment.', 'Stacy Rivera, Kendall Vanderwouw', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/854437', '', ''),
('Did u know Breast Tissue can b left behind w/Mastectomy', 'March 15th, 2016', '', '', 'Stage 1A ER+/PR+, HER2-, post double mastectomy, post double reconstruction', 'Side Effects; Masectomy Side Effects', '', 'One of the risks of a mastectomy is the fact that it is impossible to get every single bit of breast tissue, which is one of the risks that your doctor/surgeon should warn you about. ', 'Sarah Taga', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/842222', '', ''),
('Did u know Breast Tissue can b left behind w/Mastectomy', 'March 15th, 2016', '', '', 'Stage IIA ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'Side Effects; Masectomy Side Effects', '', 'There will always be some breast tissue that remains on the chest wall post bilateral mastectomies. Especially for ER+ women it is imperative that you still get AI or Tamoxifen treatments to stop BC cells and to prevent any chance of getting metasratic disease.', 'Sarah Taga', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/842222', '', ''),
('Did u know Breast Tissue can b left behind w/Mastectomy', 'March 15th, 2016', '', '', 'Stage 1A ER+/PR+, HER2-, post double mastectomy, post double reconstruction', 'Side Effects; Masectomy Side Effects', '', 'It is impossible to get all brest tissue resected but it is important to make sure that post surgery to schedule multiple followups and to continue or schedule treatments such as AI to prevent metastatic disease, regrowth or spread.', 'Sarah Taga', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/842222', '', ''),
('Chemotherapy for my Mom at Stage II-B, how to ease the pain?', 'jun 2018 ', 'how can i help my mom going through chemo?', 'going into 4th chemotheraphy out of 8. Takes CEF, but patient didn\'t mention taking Fluorouracil. ', 'Stage 2-BC', 'Side Effects; Nausea; Chemotherapy Side Effects; Encouragement ', '', 'Nausea and vomitting should be controlled, which can be done with incremental protocol with medicine or using steriods and Emend, Zofran, and Compazine before the nausea occurs. The pain from chemotherapy can be controlled with Tyleno, Aleve or Advill (which are all painkillers)  and for the joint pain, Claritin with the Neulasta or Neupogen injections. Warm baths with espom salt can also help with the pain. During chemotheraphy, food will taste terrible and you will have little appetite, but eating and drinking is important. In British Columbia, the goal during chemo is \"NO nausea or vomiting', ' which allowed the patient to have access to certain medication to allievate the pain. \"', 'Dennis Luu', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/865437', ''),
('Chemotherapy for my Mom at Stage II-B, how to ease the pain?', '', '', '', 'Stage 2B Breast Cancer entering round 4/8 of chemotherapy', 'Side Effects; Nausea; Chemotherapy Side Effects; Encouragement ', '', 'Anti-emetic drugs like Emend and Zofran and steroids can reduce nausea and vomiting. Claritin in conjunction with Neulasta or Neupogen injections can help with bone and joint pain. General pain killers should only be used after checking if the patient does not have a fever prior to taking any medicine.', 'Preetham Ramesh', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/865437', '', ''),
('Chemotherapy for my Mom at Stage II-B, how to ease the pain?', 'Febuary 2018 ', '', 'Age 54, HER2-,', 'Stage 2 breast cancer and preparing for 4th chemo out of 8.\nHas been warned to expect increasing pain upon each chemo. Takes epirubicin and cyclophosphamide\n', 'Side Effects; Nausea; Chemotherapy Side Effects; Encouragement ', '', 'Take anti-nausea drugs such as steroids and Emend, Zofran, and Compazine to mitigate effects of side-effects. In British Columbia, their objective is to prevent vomiting or nausea and would adjust medications as needed. Recommended to take Emetogenicity on day of chemo and three days after. If needed, also take OTC gravol. For pain relief, patient could take acetaminophen or ibuprofen. These should be taken after verifying the patient has no fever. If pain lingers, consider taking Tylenol 3. As an added note, warm Epsom salt baths can help with body aches as well.  ', 'Ricky Fukuyama', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/865437', '', ''),
('Chemotherapy for my Mom at Stage II-B, how to ease the pain?', 'June 25th, 2018', '', '', 'Stage IIA Grade 2, DCIS/IDC, ER+/PR+ HER2-', 'Side Effects; Nausea; Chemotherapy Side Effects; Encouragement ', '', 'For nausea scheduled steroids help, taken the day before, day of and day after chemo. Helps when taken with anti-nausea meds such as Compazine. For pain, regular pain killers such as tylenol can work. Specifically for bone pain Claritin taken with Neulasta or Neupogen injections can help. With all this little to no nausea only loss of apetite or food tastes somewhat weird. Slight aching pain but not horrible. ', 'Sarah Taga', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/865437', '', ''),
('Chemotherapy for my Mom at Stage II-B, how to ease the pain?', 'June 25th, 2018', '', '', 'Stage IIB Grade 3 IDC ER+/PR+ HER2-', 'Side Effects; Nausea; Chemotherapy Side Effects; Encouragement ', '', 'Certain medications such as Emend, Zofran or Compazine can help with nausea. Over the counter pain meds such as Tylenol, Aleve or Advil can work for pain. For both make sure to take it before the nausea or pain hits becasue then it will be too late and it wont be as effective.', 'Sarah Taga', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/865437', '', ''),
('Chemotherapy for my Mom at Stage II-B, how to ease the pain?', 'June 2018', '', '', 'Stage II BC ', 'Side Effects; Nausea; Chemotherapy Side Effects; Encouragement ', '', 'Patient is HER2- and will be having her round 4 out of 8 of chemo and was told that the 5th until the last session will be extremely painful. The patient has already experienced vomitting for 3 days after her second and third chemo sessions. She was taking epirubicin and cyclophosphamide, but was never recommended pain killers, only to maintian a healthy diet. Most patients were prescribed pain killers such as acetaminoohen, ibuprofen, Tylenol 3 (with codeine). Sense of taste may be affected so trying new drinks is recommended along with warm baths with epom salts for body aches. ', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/865437', '', ''),
('8 years ago', '', 'Did Femara bother you? AND 8 years post diagnosis; congratulations to me', '', 'Stage II, HR+, HER2-', 'Side Effects; Positive Affirmations', '', 'Femara + Lupron led to some vaginal atropy and perhaps \"head fuzziness\"\"?\"', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/849413', '', ''),
('Chemo treatment n shakiness', 'August 2017', 'Can doxorubicin and cytoxan lead to constant shakiness inside the body?', '', 'Stage 2 Breast Cancer, post-chemo, taking doxorubicin and cytoxan', 'Side Effects; Shakiness; Chemotherapy Side Effects', '', 'Doxorubicin and cytoxan chemo medicine might potentially contributed to constant feelings of shakiness 12 days after chemo treatment.', 'Kendall Vanderwouw, Smruti Vidwans, Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/857900', '', ''),
('Large tumor and lumpectomy?', 'Aug 15, 2015', 'Patient is asking if she should have a lumpectomy after recieving medicine that seems to shrink the tumor size', 'Patient undergoing taxol chemo and has seen significant tumor shrinkage', 'Stage IIB, IDC, Left, 6cm+, Grade 2, 0/2 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'Specific Condition; Lumpectomy', '', 'Taxol has significantly reduced tumor size from nearly 8cm to 3.5cm; patient is considering lumpectomy after neoadjuvant therapy for a tumor of her size. Many responders confirm it is possible and successful, and results are visually not bad or very noticeably different.', 'Valerie Chen', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/834287', '', ''),
('Just diagnosed with Stage IIb', 'January 2015', 'What is the preferred treatment method for a mass (stage II) found adjascent to lymph nodes? (Specifically: is BMX reconstruction appropriate?) (The patient is seeking advice from others with similar cases)', 'IDC, Right, 2cm, Stage IIB, Grade 2, 1/2 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2+ (IHC)', 'Stage II BC, IDC, post-MRI, (newly diagnosed)', 'Specific Condition; Reconstruction ', '', 'For triple positive patients, doctors often call for targeted treatment therapy, so BMX is in addition, (the decision depends on how patient stress tolerence).Yet, patients should consider BMX for its success against aggressive tumors. Radiation does not always accompany BMX, (although this could apply solely to patients with no node involvement). Patients warn to avoid radiation if you\'ve already had chemo, as it makes reconstruction very difficult. BRCA testing is reccomended to simplify reproductive system decisions and bring peace of mind. ', 'Kendall Vanderwouw', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/827894', '', ''),
('icromet in Sentinal Node: Anyone else?', 'October 2013', 'A micrometastis is found  in sentinal node after a unilateral mastectomy, will a second surgery for axilkary lymph node dissection be a good option?', 'Mastectomy: Right, Lymph node removal: Right, Underarm/Axillary ,Cytoxan (cyclophosphamide) Taxotere (docetaxel) chemotherapy, hormonal therapy  ', 'Stage 2B, IDC, Grade 1, 1/8 nodes ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'Specific Conditions', 'Sentinel Node', 'Many patients have seen success with chemotherapy alone with micromets up to 2.5 mm. Undergoing an ALND can help lower the chances of recurrence and maintain peace of mind. Aim to minimize the number of nodes removed to lower the risk of developing complications like lymphedema. Extra rounds of TC and radiation can be done for more insurance, and some patients prefer to meet with a physical therapist early to maintain physical wellbeing after surgery. Work with your oncologist to assess the risks and benefits of each option.', 'Amira Elfergani, Preetham Ramesh, Sara Taga', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/812581', 'edited inquiry, and rephrased insight ', ''),
('12 Week Paclitaxel?', '', '', '', 'Stage II, ER+, PR-, HER2+ ,BC, Node negative', 'Specific Conditions', '', '12 weeks paclitaxel + Herceptin (trastuzumab) corse of action for stage 2 breast cancer. After 12 week course, FEC perscribed. Typically FEC, similar to AC, used as strong chemo for stage 3. Is FEC necessary?', 'Harrison Klinski', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/867786', '', ''),
('12 Week Paclitaxel?', '', '', '', '', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'No insights  ', 'Preetham Ramesh', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/867786', '', ''),
('12 Week Paclitaxel?', '', 'Patient is inquiring if anyone received 12 weeks of paclitaxel + Herceptin (trastuzumab) as treatment for stage 2 breast cancer. ', '', '-', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'No insights?', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/867786', '', ''),
('Advice/information regarding Taxotere and Cytoxan', '', '', '', 'Stage II Breast Cancer, node-negative, high Oncotype DX score', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'Patient has high oncotype score of 34, indicating a high chance of recurrence of breast cancer post lumpectomy. Chemotherapy will make chances of recurrence lower by 5% but patient\'s daughter unsure whether side effects are worth the 5%. Ultimately, advanced technology has made side effects of chemo more managable and patient has been comfortable with treatment for four weeks', 'Jo Kuramkote', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/861303', '', ''),
('Advice/information regarding Taxotere and Cytoxan', '', '', '', 'Stage II Breast Cancer', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'Patient has had a lumpectomy (~2cm) The pathology came back node negative but her oncotype is 34. It was recommended that she do 4 rounds of Taxotere and Cytoxan, followed by 4 weeks of radiation, and then TAM. She has doubts because of her age (64) and that according to her doctor chemo will only decrease her risk of reoccurance by 5%. Patient is not sure if the 5% is worth enduring chemo.  Patient decided to start chemo after realizing she can stop treatment if she wished, and after one round is managing her symptoms pretty well. ', 'Karen Boctor', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/861303', '', ''),
('Age 33 got final path and stage IIB...need advice', '', '', '', 'Stage II BC', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'Patient was diagnosed with cancer and was doing well after surgery, and then had bad news when pathology report came in from the doctor. Surgeon had removed a 4.5cm tumor. Doctor is not too concerned but when doctor was addressed with questions the physician had said that it was a good question and will be brought up with the tumor board when presented the following week. Only treatment has been surgery and taxol so far. ', 'Jaspreet Deol', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/802893', '', ''),
('Age 33 got final path and stage IIB...need advice', '', '', '', 'Stage IIB Grade 3', 'Specific Conditions', '', '33 year old patient has undergone a bilateral masectomy. Surgeon was expecting to remove a 2-2.5cm tumor but removed 4.5cm. While the patient has early stage and her doctor is not too concerned. The patient seems to be fixiated on the size of her tumor. Patient is starting chemotherapy and possibly radiation but has concerns because effects to her heart since it is her left breast. ', 'Karen Boctor', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/802893', '', ''),
('Age 33 got final path and stage IIB...need advice', '', 'Before surgery, I was thought to have a 2.5cm tumor; after surgery it is 4.5cm with micromets in sentinel node. I am freaking out. Any encouraging stories?', '', 'Stage II BC', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'No insight?', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/802893', '', ''),
('ALND for micromet?', 'October 2015', '', '', 'Stage IIA BC, invasive ductal carcinoma, Grade 1, ER+/PR+, HER2- (FISH)', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'Radiation treatment is the preferred treatment rather than ALND among patients due to, at least for this patient, intense down stream consequences of the surgery, such as a harder time lifting heavy objects. In addition it appears that for the cases where the patient\'s doctor reccomend ALND at first for micromet they eventually switch over to radiation, as such it is reccommended to pursue radiation as a more painless and cost-less treatment', 'Daniel Chen', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/836282', '', ''),
('ALND for micromet?', 'Began October 2015', '', '', 'Stage 2 Breast Cancer, IDC, post-Mastectomy and lymph node removal', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'Despite traditional recommendation for ALDN by MOs, many patients choose radiation, given ALDN\'s risk of lymphedema and possible nerve damage. Patients  favor radiation for a micromet as it is cheaper, although patients warn of a possibility of recurrence connected to DNA mutation in breast cells resulting from radiation. ', 'Kendall Vanderwouw', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/836282', '', ''),
('ALND for micromet?', 'November 2015', 'Patient believes her doctors are providing disagreeing opinions is asking about what kind of questions she should ask based on her specific condition', '', 'Stage II BC with micromets', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'ALND typically recommended for lymph node involvement/ micromet post surgery. However it carries risk of lymphedema and recently (2015) radiation is starting to be recommended instead.', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/836282', '', ''),
('Anxious about the port..', 'March 2015', '', '', 'DCIS Stage 0 Grade 3 ER+/PR-, HER2+', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'Using the port is reccommended as many people using IV have negative side affects (such as messing with your vein), the surgery is usually very easy and heals well, you may feel it but ther is relatively no pain or discomfort, and as you will usually have a miniumum of 17 infusions port is stonrgly reccommended rather than IV, saving you a lot of discomfort and problems.', 'Daniel Chen', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/829140', '', ''),
('Anxious about the port..', '', '', '', 'DCIS, 2cm, Stage 0, Grade 3, ER+/PR-, HER2-', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'Worried about chemo port infection. Port seems to be best method for drug administering, due to strength of chemo and deteriorating affects on veins (non-IV). Possible alternatives to chemo port?', 'Harrison Klinski', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/829140', '', ''),
('Anxious about the port..', 'March 2015', 'Patient is anxious regarding about the port for chemotherapy', '', 'Stage II, HR+ and HER2+', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'Port recommended over IV for HER2+ disease given the large number of treatments required. IV can cause \'deterioration\' of veins. Be vigilant for symptoms associated with ports. While most are minor, some could be reflective of infection or malfunctioning ports. ', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/829140', '', ''),
('Anxious about the port..', 'March 2015', '', '', 'DCIS, 2cm,Stage 0, Grade 3, ER+/PR-, HER2-', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'Patient is feeling anxious about developing an infection on the port. Most patients have had positive experiences using the port since it alleviates stressing about whether you have had enough water and if your veins are good enough for IV treatment. ', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/829140', '', ''),
('Anybody have stage 2B IDC Cancer with very low oncotype score?', '', '', '', 'Invasive Ductal Cancer stage 2B', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'Patient had a lumpectomy with sentinel lymph node biopsy with findings of 3 sentinel lymph nodes positive for cancer. After that I had a level 1 and level 2 axillary lymph node dissection with complete negative findings. her onco type score was only 7. Also had a negative PET/CT scan for metastasis. Many of the oncologists are now reccomending lympectomies instead of mastectomies.', 'Sharan K. G.', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/818536', '', ''),
('Anybody have stage 2B IDC Cancer with very low oncotype score?', 'February 2014', '', '', '-', 'Specific Conditions', '', '<MIGHT HOLD OFF ON THIS BECAUSE THE DISCUSSION AROUND TREATMENT DECISION IS >5 years old AND THERE HAVE BEEN SEVERAL ADVANCES SINCE THEN>', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/818536', '', ''),
('Anybody have stage 2B IDC Cancer with very low oncotype score?', 'Feb 2014', '', '', 'Invasive Ductal Cancer stage 2B', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'Patient firstly had a lumpectomy with sentinel lymph node biopsy with findings of 3 sentinel lymph nodes positive for cancer. Later, this patient had a level 1 and level 2 axillary lymph node dissection with complete negative findings, and had a negative PET/CT scan for metastasis. ', 'Snow Wu', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/818536', '', ''),
('Anyone diagnosed IDC-L?', '', '', '', 'Stage 2A IDC w/ Lobular features', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'Invasive ductoral carcenoma with lobular features has unclear nature but seems to be not that different from IDC. Responds to Als better than Tamoxifen but depends on MO to assess which drug treatment is optimal. Negative E-cadherin stain indicated that IDC was lobular', 'Jo Kuramkote', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/864439', '', ''),
('Anyone diagnosed IDC-L?', 'May \'18', '', '', 'Stage 2A IDC w/ Lobular features', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'Presence of lobular cancer is signified by a negative E-cadherin stain. ILC and IDC are treated simlarly but each responds to different drugs differently. It is up to the MO to decide which is best. ', 'Preetham Ramesh', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/864439', '', ''),
('Anyone diagnosed IDC-L?', '', 'Patient is asking regarding her specific situation and what it entails based on what other patients have experienced', '', 'Stage II IDC with lobular features', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'IDC with lobular features treated similar to IDC \n\nLobular nature was based on e-cadherin negative stain\n\nILC responds better to AIs than to Tamoxifen (ALL NEED TO BE VERIFIED)\n', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/864439', '', 'NEEDS TO BE VERIFIE'),
('Anyone ever see Elevated CA 27/29 with a respiratory infection?', '', '', '', 'Stage II BC', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'It is normal to see a jump in CA 27.29 as it is caused by many factors such as illnesses and surgery. ', 'Hamza Hussain', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/845223', '', ''),
('Anyone ever see Elevated CA 27/29 with a respiratory infection?', 'May \'06', '', '', 'Stage 2 BC just received Prolia shot', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'Illness and inflammation can cause a jump in cancer antigen 27-29 number but they will drop once the illness is dealt with. ', 'Preetham Ramesh', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/845223', '', ''),
('Anyone ever see Elevated CA 27/29 with a respiratory infection?', 'June 2016', 'Patient has had her CA almost doubled and nasal discharge due to traveling and is asking if anyone has encountered this situation  ', '', 'Stage II BC (or more general than that)', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'CA 27/29 is a breast cancer marker. But it can also be high because of other factors like illnesses and surgery', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/845223', '', ''),
('Anyone have a low Onco type dx with positive lymph nodes???', 'August 10th, 2014', '', '', 'Stage IA on the right and Stage IIA on the left, ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'Having positive lymph nodes and low oncotype DX used to be an immediate indicator for needing chemo, but now treatments have changed with research. Patients with oncotype as low as 4 have seen success without chemotherapy. Menstruation can stop or occur as low as once a year when on Tamoxifen which is normal.', 'Sarah Taga', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/823546', '', ''),
('Anyone have a low Onco type dx with positive lymph nodes???', 'August 2014', '', '', '-', 'Specific Conditions', '', '<MIGHT HOLD OFF ON THIS BECAUSE THE DISCUSSION AROUND TREATMENT DECISION IS >5 years old AND THERE HAVE BEEN SEVERAL ADVANCES SINCE THEN>', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/823546', '', ''),
('Anyone have a low Onco type dx with positive lymph nodes???', '', '', '', 'Low Onco dx with positive lymph nodes', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'This patient had Onco score 12 and a 1.9cm tumor with 2 lymph nodes micro invasion. Highly ER/PR positive, HER negative. All the results indicated her tumor is considered as Grade 1. The patient questioned if it\'s ok to not receive chemotherapy and felt concerned about insisting on taking tamoxifen because she had not gotten her period since after she got her period in June.', 'Snow Wu', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/823546', '', ''),
('Balloon Sinuplasty info', '', '', '', 'Stage 2 IDC', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'Balloon sinuplast surgery seems to be successful in ridding patients of sinusitis symptoms such as headaches', 'Jo Kuramkote', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/816882', '', ''),
('Balloon Sinuplasty info', 'Jan \'14', '', '', '?', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'Balloon sinuplasty can provide patients with chronic sinusitis immediate relief. (Not sure if the sinusitis is due to BC or treatment)', 'Preetham Ramesh', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/816882', '', ''),
('Balloon Sinuplasty info', 'January 2014', 'Patient is going for a Balloon Sinuplasty surgery and is asking about the experience', '', '-', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'No insights about breast cancer', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/816882', '', ''),
('Breast Cancer - you\'re kidding me!', '', '', '', 'Stage II BC', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'Advil can take care of joint pain due to hormone blockers. Additionally, if you think you are done with more surgeries be done and you can reconsider late down the road of you like to go through more surgical procedures. ', 'Hamza Hussain', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/832185', '', ''),
('Breast Cancer - you\'re kidding me!', 'May \'15', '', '', 'Stage 2 BC', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'Joint pain caused by hormone blockers can be alleviated by taking advil.', 'Preetham Ramesh', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/832185', '', ''),
('Breast Cancer - you\'re kidding me!', 'May \'15', '', '', 'Stage 2 BC', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'Has had several (28) radiation treatments which has caused the breast that had the radiation, to be much smaller which is due to muscle and skin damage. The hormone blockers are causing joint pain. It is recommended to take Advil gel caps to help with joint inflammation. ', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/832185', '', ''),
('Did you have hormone blocker during adjuvant chemo?', 'November 28th, 2017', '', '', '', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'Patient wants to know if any other patients has had adjuvent hormone blocker during the stages of adjuvant chemotherapy. Patient is worried about any cells being exposed for 10 weeks during first and second dose of AC (post op dose)', 'Christina Ton ', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/860463', '', ''),
('Did you have hormone blocker during adjuvant chemo?', 'November 2017', 'Has anybody had hormone therapy before or along with chemotherapy?', '-', '-', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'No insights', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/860463', '', ''),
('Did you have hormone blocker during adjuvant chemo?', 'November 28th, 2017', '', '', 'Stage II Breast Cancer', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'Patient has cancer of grade 3, multifocal. She has not had her period after the second dose of AC, so she is suspecting that chemopause reduced estrogen. She wondered if anyone had any hormone therapy prior to or while on chemo.', 'Zihan Zheng', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/860463', '', ''),
('False-Negative Sentinel Node Biopsy', 'June 2016', '', 'ATM gene mutation, Lynch Syndrome, On HRT for 17 years at dx. Oncotype 19, MammaPrint high-risk. Ki67 29.1% ER 90% PR 5% False-negative sentinel node biopsy', 'Stage 2 BC', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'There is no certain way to tell if a node is a new one or a recurrence. Patients looked towards a second opinion OR physicians prescribed a different treatement. ', 'Hamza Hussain', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/845296', '', ''),
('False-Negative Sentinel Node Biopsy', 'June 2016', 'Is a false negative SNB because of a local/ regional recurrence?', '', 'Stage 2, SNB negative, lymph node +', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'A negative SNB doesn\'t always mean no nodal involvement (SNB 90-95% accurate). NEED TO VALIDATE', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/845296', '', ''),
('False-Negative Sentinel Node Biopsy', 'June 20th, 2016', '', '', 'Stage II BC, ATM gene mutation, Lynch Syndrome ', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'This patient recieved a false negative result from a Sentinel Node Biopsy. They discovered an enlarged node in the shower. They are conflicted on whether this is considered as a logical/ regional recurrence. Other patients explain that they have had similar experiences where in the OR, their SNB was positive but in the lab it was found to be positive with 20 IST. They then recieved ALND  due to her Her2+  status. ', 'Stacy Rivera ', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/845296', '', ''),
('how do u know cancer hasnt spread despite clear nrgins?', '', 'Patient is concerned about the risk of the BC metastasizing ', 'Patient had lumpectomy leading to clear nodes, but worries about risk of metastasis somewhere other than the breasts. Pathology reports say that her cells are irregular/aggressive. ', 'Stage 2 Breast Cancer', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'Responder said that there is no real way to know for sure if cancer is all gone even after clear CT/PET, and it is best to just accept that and try to live your life at some point.', 'Devansh Dwivedy', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/812767', '', ''),
('how do u know cancer hasnt spread despite clear nrgins?', 'October 12, 2013', '', '', 'Stage 2 Breast Cancer', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'The truth is, that there is no way to know for sure. Even with clear CTs and PETs, there is a possibility that there is a small amount of cancer. It is recommeneded to just llive your life & not allow those thoughts to consume you. ', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/812767', '', ''),
('how do u know cancer hasnt spread despite clear nrgins?', '', '', '', 'Stage 2 Breast Cancer', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'Even when patients get clear CTs and PETs there can still be cancer that is too small to detect. The patient is advised to continue to live their life and not to worry about it.', 'Deepthi Mohanraj', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/812767', '', ''),
('Intramammary node positive no big deal?', 'February 12, 2018', 'Patient has been told by the physician that an intramammary node positive is not a big deal and the patient wants to ensure this is true', '', 'Stage IIB, ILC, Right, 4cm, Grade 2, 1/2 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2- ', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'From previous experience, a patient responds that it was not a big deal since it was not in the axillary chain. It is suggested to not look it up on the internet since it can cause more anxiety since all the information is outdated. ', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/862419', '', ''),
('Intramammary node positive no big deal?', '', '', '', '', 'Specific Conditions', '', '', 'Jaspreet Deol', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/862419', '', ''),
('Intramammary node positive no big deal?', 'February 2018', 'Is an intramammary node positive after umx a big deal?', '', 'Stage 2 BC, ILC, Right, 4cm, Stage IIB, Grade 2, 1/2 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2- (FISH)', 'Specific Conditions', 'Intramammary node postitives', 'Patients worry about postitive intramammary nodes, and should acknowledge that radiation is not necessary because the cancer does not reside in the axillar chains. Patients note that online resources advertise outdated research.', 'Kendall Vanderwouw', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/862419', '', ''),
('Looking for opinions and info', '', '', '', '', 'Specific Conditions', '', '', '', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/846275', '', ''),
('Lump discovered while on chemo', 'December 14, 2015', 'Patient is concerned regarding lumps she feels after getting cancer surgery. Patient is asking if these can be due to fibroadenoma removed during the surgery. ', 'Right, 2cm, Grade 3. 0/12 nodes, ER-/PR-, HER2-. 2 cm of fibroadenoma removed.', 'Post surgery', 'Specific Conditions', 'Lumps, Scar tissue', 'Patients have said that it might be a scar tissue that is being felt instead of a lump that can arise any concern. MRI is highly recommended . ', 'Hamza Hussain', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/838496', '', ''),
('lung nodules, thyroid nodules---help!!!', '', 'Patient is concerned about a 6-7 mm lung nodule. ', 'ILC, 2cm, Stage IIA, Grade 2, 0/1 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'Stage IIA BC(ILC)', 'Specific Conditions', '', 'Patient is concerned about a 6-7 mm lung nodule. Went to get it checked and physician said it was very small and most likely benign. Other patients in the forum discussed having similar nodules that were found to be benign. Minor health complications can be amplified for BC patients and appears to add additional stress.', 'Abigail Mendoza', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/821509', '', ''),
('Advice/information regarding Taxotere and Cytoxan', '', 'Should my mom with a specific profile (High Oncotype) get chemo (4 rounds of Cytoxan and Taxotere)?', '', 'Stage II Breast Cancer, node-negative, high Oncotype DX score', 'Specific Conditions \n\n(I think it might be \'Right Treatment\': SJV)', '', 'Elderly (~70 yr) patient with node-negative BC but with high Oncotype DX recurrence score (34) should undergo chemotherapy. ', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/861303', '', ''),
('Incomplete response to chemo - hormone positive', 'June 7th 2019', 'Patient is doing ACT and after the third dose sees that she is responding, but not as well as she\'d like. She wonder if anyone had a mediocre response to neoadjuvant chemo and still done okay.', '', 'Stage 2 Breast Cancer', 'Specific Conditions; Chemotherapy', '', 'Responders point out that more treatments such as chemo and surgery may help further as treatment even if respnse to ACT isn\'t stellar.', 'Devansh Dwivedy', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/871953', '', ''),
('Incomplete response to chemo - hormone positive', '6.7/2019', '', '', 'Stage 2 BC', 'Specific Conditions; Chemotherapy', '', 'She does not have an amazing response to the ACT that she has taken three doses. A responder points out that she may have more treatments to go through. Surgery and radiation will take care of the remaining things, if any.', 'Zihan Zheng', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/871953', '', ''),
('Low Oncotype score VS Pathology findings', 'September 11, 2016', 'Patient is wondering if others have experienced a low onco score with aggressive pathology features', '41 yrs old, 3.8 cm, Grade 3, Extensive lymphovascular invasion, clear nodes and margins, after surgery another mass of 1.3 cm was discovered, oncotype score = 8, doctors are unicertain if the 2nd smaller mass was connected to the larger mass (3.8 cm) ', 'Stage IIA BC, IDC, Right, 3 cm, Grade 3, 0/5 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2- ', 'Specific Conditions; Comparing Therapies; Chemotherapy', '', 'It is said this situation is no different from a lumpectomy having unlcean margins. Although chemotherapy is one of the harshest treatments, it is not recommended to do it just to say they\'ve done everything possible. A patient recommended that with a grade tumor of that size, they should undergo chemo despite the oncotype score especially since they have the LVI. ', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/847961', '', ''),
('Low Oncotype, node-positive and chemo decision', '', '', '', 'Stage 2 breast cancer, post-lumpectomy with newly discovered cancer spread to node', 'Specific Conditions; Comparing Therapies; Chemotherapy', '', 'First, there is no easy answer for the question about whether to take chemotherapy or not. Factors considered by some included Oncotype Dx score, tolerance for side effects (hair loss) and life goals (some with young kids wanted to hit the cancer as hard as possible). Taxol seems to have less hair loss', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/859730', '', 'Chemotherapy agents Taxotere and Taxol are both taxanes. Taxol has been used extensively in the treatment of breast cancer; Taxotere is a newer chemotherapy agent that kills cancer cells in a similar manner.'),
('Low Oncotype, node-positive and chemo decision', 'October 2017', 'Is chemotherapy preferable to Taxol/Cytoxan?', '', 'Stage 2 BC, positive nodes post-lumpectomy', 'Specific Conditions; Comparing Therapies; Chemotherapy', 'Taxol/Cytoxan', 'Patients struggle to choose between chemo and alternatives. Patients often consider Oncotype score, number of involved nodes, and hormone positivity before choosing a treatment option. Patients should consider that chemo\'s aggressiveness can bring lifelong health risks and hairloss post-treatment (and patients with low Oncotype scores may not want to invoke risks, although Taxol appears to prevent some hairloss).', 'Kendall Vanderwouw', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/859730', '', ''),
('Did anyone have a CT or PET scan early on?', 'November 29th, 2014', '', '', 'Stage IIA, IDC', 'Specific Conditions; Early CT/PET', '', 'Patient inquired about getting full scans early on to detect any and all present nodules or mets. Though some said that the early scans would help ease the psychological toil of the cancer it was reccommended that the patient follows regular protocol as called upon by doctors and oncologists. Unnecessary scans can be frightening due to the reveal of mets that turn out to be benign and some insurance companies wont cover all the scans. Also, some doctors wont allow scans without any standing evidence that ther could be something wrong such as pain or lumps.', 'Sarah Taga', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/826639', '', ''),
('Did anyone have a CT or PET scan early on?', 'November 29th, 2014', '', '', 'Stage IIA, IDC', 'Specific Conditions; Early CT/PET', '', 'Question posed on whether or not it would be beneficial to the patients to get early scans to make sure all cancerous mets can be detected. Reccommended to listen to your MO\'s or oncologist\'s advice by only scanning when lumps are present or prolonged pain. Too many early or unnecesary scans can show false positives and will often not change standard of care.', 'Sarah Taga', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/826639', '', ''),
('Did anyone have a CT or PET scan early on?', 'November 2014', 'I\'m concerned that I am not getting diagnostic scan (PET or CT) prior to chemo. I just got an MRI. Any experience with this?', '', '', 'Specific Conditions; Early CT/PET', '', 'There does not seem to be a standard protocol around use of diagnostic imaging prior to treatment. Some reasons not to do imaging are cost/ insurance and impact of radiation. ', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/826639', '', 'SHOULD LOOK TO SEE IF THERE IS A STANDARD PROTOCOL! '),
('Did anyone have a CT or PET scan early on?', 'Nov 29th, 2014', '', '', 'Stage II Breast Cancer', 'Specific Conditions; Early CT/PET', '', 'Patient was panic because she heard that some women got full scans early on but she did not. She was wondering if she needed to have a CT or pet scan prior to chemo. Additional, she was frustrated with her consistant paranoia of cancer.', 'Zihan Zheng', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/826639', '', ''),
('Ladies - I need some advice on Stage II Breast Cancer', 'January 18, 2014', 'Patient is concerned about a relative who is not giving full extent of her illness only hints. She is trying to decipher what kind of BC she has. ', '', 'friend of hers is Stage II BC', 'Specific Conditions; Encouragement', '', 'Most of the symptoms are inconsistent, but one must keep in mind that the patient might be in shock or since they were recently diagnosed they are working with different doctors, trying to find the best treatment for them. It is suggested that perhaps the patient confused the medication, Taxotere for Tamoxefen which is making them lose their hair. Also the reason why the patient may have not had surgery at stage II is because a very small tumor can be removed using sentinel node biopsy with nodal involvment. Chemo pill can also be an alternative to surgery in order to get rid of a small tumor.', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/817065', '', ''),
('Ladies - I need some advice on Stage II Breast Cancer', 'January 2014', 'Is there a significant reason why someone afflicted with Stage II BC in sentinel node (and 3 lymph nodes) would not have surgery?', '', 'Stage II BC, no surgery, (a relative of the comment\'s author)', 'Specific Conditions; Encouragement', '', 'An uncommon alternative to surgery for a tiny stage II tumor is a sentinel node biospy, although surgery is more common among patients. Patients should consider that Taxotere often leads to hairloss, while Tamoxefen often does not. Inconsistencies in treatment are common, although average spans of radiation treatment are 5-6 weeks (-33 sessions). Patients can also ingest a chemo pill, which can conquer a small tumor, as an alternative to surgical methods.', 'Kendall Vanderwouw', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/817065', '', ''),
('experience high ki67 and grade 3', 'July 13, 2018', '', '', 'Stage II Breast Cancer', 'Specific Conditions; High ki67, Grade 3', '', 'Patient, after neo adjuvant chemo, was informed by their consultant that a positive node was found that had a 70% ki 67, which is a grade of 3 >20%. So, pt has a high calculated recurrence rate of about 20-30%, an important factor into deciding a treatment plan and is asking for advice/experience. Other patients suggested that proper exercise/lifestyle changes can help to drop her risk but stongly suggest meeting with a counselor to address remaining concerns.', 'Geon Kim', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/865859', '', ''),
('experience high ki67 and grade 3', 'November 2017', '', 'Dx 9/14/2017,IDC, Right, 2.5 - 3 cm, stage 2, ER+/PR+, HER2- chemo: 12/11/2017 ( FEC-T protocol )', 'Stage 2 BC', 'Specific Conditions; High ki67, Grade 3', '', 'Most of these recurence rates are just statistics they do not reflect what will happend 100% of the time. Also it is a good idea to consult a councillor if negative and converned thoughts are taking over as they only make you worry more. Patients have also suggest some \"Predictor\"\" calculators which take into account the ki67 number and then determine the what your chance of recurrence is. \"', 'Hamza Hussain', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/865859', '', ''),
('experience high ki67 and grade 3', 'July 2018', 'Patient is worried about a Stage 3 diagnosis with a high ki67 score', '', 'HR+, ki67 is 70%, grade 3', 'Specific Conditions; High ki67, Grade 3', '', '\"Physical activity can reduce breast cancer mortality by about 40% and has the most powerful effect of any lifestyle factor on breast cancer outcomes.\"\" http://www.cmaj.ca/content/cmaj/189/7/E268.full.pd...\"', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/865859', '', ''),
('Liver mets or Benign Hemangioma?', 'December 12, 2017', 'Confused by the results of her ultrasound and wondering why the size of the lesion is about the same size as the tumor that was removed, can they grow that fast from the breast into the liver?', 'Patient had a masectomy, 2 days after their surgery they had an ultrasound', 'Stage IIB, IDC, grade3, HER2+', 'Specific Conditions; Liver Mets', '', 'Fatty liver is usually common and usually benign. There is a forrum for this specific question called \"Not diagnosed with mets', ' but worried\"\" which could help answer their questions in further details \"', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/860804', ''),
('Did u know Breast Tissue can b left behind w/Mastectomy', 'March 2016', 'I\'m frustrated that I\'m going to have to do tamoxifen even after double mastectomy because some tissue could always be left behind. If I had know I would have had different kind of surgery.', '', 'Stage II, ER+, HER2-', 'Specific Conditions; Masectomy, Residual Tissue', '', 'Breast cancer cells can always be left behind after mastectomy. Mastectomy is not curative, which is why it is often followed by other treatment modalities such as chemo or hormone therapy', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/842222', '', ''),
('Just diagnosed with stage 2a breast cancer', '', '', '', 'Just diagnosed, 2A breast cancer, about to have surgery', 'Specific Conditions; New Diagnosis', '', 'Patients are concerned about whether waiting for 2 months for surgery (removal of lymph nodes, Lumpectomy, sentinel node, bilateral masectomy) will impact treatment outcome. Patients with: ER+, ER-, PR+, ER-, HER2+, HER2-, ', 'Christina Ton', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/862639', '', ''),
('Just diagnosed with stage 2a breast cancer', '', '', '', 'Diagnosed with stage 2a Breast Cancer and expecting surgery', 'Specific Conditions; New Diagnosis', '', 'Patient tested positive for a cancerous lump, stage 2a 1.5cm lump. She is estrogen reptor positive and progesteron receptor positive. Patient is scheduled for a lumpectomy in 2 months but is worried that it is a long time to wait. After further research, most other patients confirm that waiting a while is completely normal due to the nature of cancer not growing very quickly. Furthermore, she is attending a wedding coming up soon and is worried about irritating the surgery. Other patients ensure that their post-lumpectomy experience was relatively painless and should not cause a disruption in day-to-day life.', 'Geon Kim', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/862639', '', ''),
('Just diagnosed with stage 2a breast cancer', '', 'Patient is concerned about whether waiting for 2 months for surgery will impact treatment outcome', '', 'newly diagnosed, pre-treatment stage 2', 'Specific Conditions; New Diagnosis', '', '2 months between diagnosis and treatment does not impact outcome.\"Its more of an emotional rather than medical emergency\"\". More information at: https://respectfulinsolence.com/2016/01/12/breast-cancer-and-delays-in-surgery/\"', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/862639', '', ''),
('Just diagnosed with stage 2a breast cancer', 'February 2018', 'Will delaying treatment two months have a negative effect on treatment results?', '', 'Stage II BC, pre-lumpectomy, pre-sentinel node biopsy', 'Specific Conditions; New Diagnosis', '', 'Delaying treatment two months is not irregular, and does not have a significant effect on the results of treatment, (the cancer does not grow quickly enough for two months to be significant).', 'Kendall Vanderwouw', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/862639', 'add the patient profile ', ''),
('I need help! Calling all Stage 2a Oncotype dx 22', 'May 14th/ 2017', 'Patient is asking if walking away from Tamoxifen post-surgery is a good idea', '', 'Stage 2a Oncotype dx 22', 'Specific Conditions; Oncotype Score; Tamoxifen ', '', 'Taking out the ovary can make a patient mastasize into spine and dye a few years later after a very painful life.', '', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/804661', '', ''),
('I need help! Calling all Stage 2a Oncotype dx 22', 'May 2013', '', '', 'Stage 2a ', 'Specific Conditions; Oncotype Score; Tamoxifen ', '', 'Patient was advised to not take Tamoxifen due to a clotting risk factor. Other patients have used Aromasin as there is no clotting risk. Her Medical Oncologist suggested removing ovaries, which would make her less liable for bone melts. ', 'Katherine Brizuela', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/804661', '', ''),
('I need help! Calling all Stage 2a Oncotype dx 22', 'May 2013', 'I can\'t take chemo. Will taking out my ovaries to push me into menopause make a difference in my physical health and recurrence rate?', 'Lymph node removal: Right; Mastectomy: Left, Right; Reconstruction (left): DIEP flap, Tissue expander placement; Reconstruction (right): DIEP flap, Tissue expander placement. 14% recurrence probability (presuming that estrogen depresser are taken), two genes that risk clotting, pre-menopausal ', 'IDC, 2cm, Stage IIA, Grade 2, 0/1 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'Specific Conditions; Oncotype Score; Tamoxifen ', '', 'In the pre-menopausal phase, having your ovaries removed would make you much less liable to developing bone mets. This procedure can be followed by chemotherapy to decrease the risk of recurrence. Aromasin can be used instead of Tamoxifen since it doesnt present a clotting risk. In regards to calculating your recurrence risk without an estrogen inhibitor, it is roughly double than that if taking one. \n', 'Amira Elfergani ', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/804661', '', ''),
('Can anyone help me discern?', 'February 2018', '', '', 'Stage 2A IDC', 'Specific Conditions; Postive Nodes; Distant Metastases', '', 'It is possible to have positive nodes and not have distant metastasis, often regional nodes are looked at to detmerine course of treatment. Extra-capsular extension means outside the wall of then node and not having this is considered a good thing. After treatment such as chemo or surgery for the nodes, people did not have distant metastasis', 'Deepthi Mohanraj', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/862385', '', ''),
('Can anyone help me discern?', 'February 2018', 'Does getting a node biopsy guarantee distant metastasis?', '', 'Stage II BC post chemotherapy and lumpectomy, HER2+', 'Specific Conditions; Postive Nodes; Distant Metastases', '', 'Patients from a variety of cancer stages often worry about the possibility of distant metastasis from their node biopsy, although one should note that distant metasis is not guarenteed. ', 'Kendall Vanderwouw', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/862385', '', ''),
('Can anyone help me discern?', 'February 2018', 'Patient is concerned regarding distant mestastasis based on her specific condition.', '', 'Stage II', 'Specific Conditions; Postive Nodes; Distant Metastases', '', 'It is possible to have positive nodes without having distant metastases', 'Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/862385', '', ''),
('Increased uptake in cervical,thorasic knee and ankle', 'April 22, 2014', 'can previous spine surgeries cause an increased uptake in cervical, thorasic spine, knee and ankle? or is it cancer?', 'Lumpectomy: Right; Lymph node removal: Right, Sentinel, CMF chemotherapy, hormonal therapy, radiations, cervical fusion, acl repair scolosis in thorasic spine', 'Stage 2A BC, IDC, 3cm, Grade 3. 0/2 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'Specific Conditions; Side Effects', 'Arthritis', 'Usually this is due to arthritis in those specific areas rather then a big concern. This is common as it comes with age and previous injuries that one may have had. A bone scan explain this in greater detail. ', 'Hamza Hussain, Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/820441', 'edited patient profile, cohort, and inquiry ', ''),
('Decisions re: ovaries/estrogen', 'May 2014', '', '', 'Stage 2 ER/PR+', 'Specific Therapy Inquiries', '', '', '', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/821080', '', ''),
('Follow up protocol?', 'August 2018', 'Patient is concerned regarding a follow up MRI after getting active treatments and thinks that the physician is not being transparent', '', 'Stage IIB, IDC, Grade 1 Right only  ER+/PR+, HER2-, post lumpectomy, post active treatment ', 'Specific Therapy Inquiries', '', 'MRIs are used by some physicians to monitor recurrence after surgery instead of say, \'watch and wait\'. With MRI, disease progression can be detected before symptoms appear. It has also been known that routine MRIs are common post-lumpectomy procedure.', 'Deepthi Mohanraj, Dennis Luu, Devansh Dwivedy, Kendall Vanderwouw, Smruti Vidwans, Sarah Taga ', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/866347', '', 'Insight: MRI used by some physicians to monitor recurrence after surgery instead of say, \'watch and wait\'. With MRI, disease progression can be detected before symptoms appear. A good thing to follow up on here is to see if we can parse why some doctors go with MRIs and some don\'t. Does it have to do with the specifics of the cancer? Do the NCCN guidelines say anything about this? Is it related to reimbursement (insurance coverage) or something else?'),
('About to start Radiation ... Need advice on what to expect', 'Dec 2016', 'what can i expect going into radiation?', '30 sessions radiation, left breast ', '', 'Specific Therapy Inquries', 'Radiation ', 'The actual treatment is quick but the positioning takes the longest. Make sure to know who is in charge to ask questions when needed. On the first day, position of radiation typically marked with small tattoos but you can ask about being marked by Sharpies. It can get a bit lonely in the radiation room alone make sure to give yourself a pep talk beforehand. There is a few days of tiredness and some people might experience skin breakage and rash, but the nurses always patch those up. ', 'Hamza Hussain, Linh Nguyen, Preetham Ramesh, Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/851184', '', ''),
('Afinitor Trial for Stage 2', 'Dec 2017 ', 'I just started the clinical trial of Afintor/Letrozole just wondering if anyone else is doing the same. How your feeling and when to expect any side effects.', 'Afintor/Letrozole clinical trial', ' Stage IIA, grade 2, Node+, HR+, HER2-, high chance of recurrence.', 'Specific Therapy Inquries', '[Trial #?]', 'Consider clinical trial (Afinitor/ Letrozole) if high chance of recurrence. (Recurrence tests include Oncotype DX, BCI and Nottingham score)', 'Sharan K. G. , Smruti Vidwans', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/861216', '', ''),
