('Malat 1 results', 'January 12, 2016', 'asking for opinions on the Malat 1 research', 'had a lymph node removal: Sentinel, Masectomy: Left, Right; Prophylactic masectomy: Left ', 'Stage IIA, IDC, Right, 2 cm, Grade 2, 0/2 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-', '', '', 'the research reminded a patient of an article about Beta-gluca and how it can prevent tamoxifen-resistant cell growth. They decided to take the supplements since they dont have real side effects.', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/839907', '', ''),
('Malat 1 results', 'Jan 2016 ', 'asking for thoughts on the Malat 1 research', 'had a sentinal lymph node removal, double masectomy, left prophylactic masectomy, prophylactic ovary removal, and reconstruction. She also has done chemotherapy and hormonal therapy.', 'IDC, Right, 2cm, Stage IIA, Grade 2, 0/2 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-', '', '', 'The research motivates some patients to take the beta-gluca supplements, to prevent tamoxifen-resistant cell growth, since they dont have real side effects.', 'Amira Elfergani', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/839907', '', ''),
('Male breast cancer', 'March 31, 2017', 'would like to hear from men diagnosed with BC and their course of treatment and prognosis', 'male diagnosed with BC, removed 1.7 cm tumor', 'Stage II BC, IDC, HER2+', '', '', 'There is a forum recommended specifically for men diagnosed with BC, called \"Male Breast Cancer Forum\"\". After chemo', ' it is recommended to do some slight exercise', ' since it can help with recovery. The anti nausea drugs will help with the fatigue side effect. \"', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/853864'),
('Mastectomy one or both?', 'November 10, 2017', 'Patient is having a masectomy and would like to hear of different options', 'Had multiple positive lymph nodes and a tumor in left breast', 'Stage II BC, ICD, triple negative, no BRCA gene', '', '', 'Patient believes it would be simpler to remove both breasts to be on the safe side as well to make it easier in the long run for cosmetic purposes. ', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/860018', '', ''),
('Mastectomy one or both?', 'Nov 2017', 'patient needs help choosing between a single and a double masectomy ', 'considering a mastectomy for a tumor in left breast with multiple positive lymph nodes ', 'Stage II BC, ICD, triple negative, no BRCA gene', '', '', 'In cases of invasive tumors, a double mastectomy can free you the constant worrying of a recurrence. It will also make a later breast reconstruction easier and more likely to produce matching breasts.', 'Amira Elfergani', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/860018', '', ''),
('Mastectomy without radiation... why?', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/826912', '', ''),
('MD Anderson VS Moffitt Cancer center', 'March 27, 2017 ', 'want opinions from anyone who has done their own research on where to get the best medical help or have had experiences with cancer centers (Moffitt). Also looking for different recommendations', 'her mother had a masectomy in march and the results came back with positive nodes, but the doctor cant see her until a week later. was originally diagnosed via biopsy in january', 'Stage II BC', '', '', 'The patient who traveled to MD Anderson found it to be a very reassuring experience, where they were able to request mostly women on their team. Moffitt is thought to be good also, but one pateint described their experience as \"horrible\"\" since theywould have long wait times. It is normal to wait severak weeks after surgery to be seen by an oncologist since they want you to be recovered from surgery before chemo starts. MDA is thought to be the best option if you have a difficult cancer. \"', 'Stacy Rivera', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/853763', '', ''),
('Megastrol 20 mg or Combustion', 'December 3, 2014', 'Asking for experiences taking Megestrol for hot flashes ', 'Patient is experiencing hot flashes so their MD put her on Megastrol 20 mg daily.  ', 'Stage II BC, IDC, 3 cm, Grade 1, 0/1 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-, hot flashes, side effects of Megastrol', 'side effects management', '', 'Another possibility to manage hot flashes is clonidine, especially if patient also need to address high blood pressure. Gabapentin works for a patients heat, but made them spacey and tired at first and at larger doses. Taking it in the evenings is best. The patient later said that Megace (Megestrol) is working and their hot flashes are down 1-3 mild ones although they still get chills from time to time. Another patient said this drug saved their life although it does increase apetite.', 'Stacy Rivera, Amira Elfergani,  Zihan Zheng', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/826728', '', ''),
('Met my MD\'s .. have a plan....', 'June 3, 2017', 'Just want to share her story', 'She is Stage 2a 1.7 tumor with one node known to be involved. It is Grade High/3, which means it\'s aggressive, but her MD feels that she is still in early stage of breast cancer. She is also Triple positive ', 'State 2a, Grade High/3', '', '', 'She finally have hope in this long journey of fighting against breast cancer', 'Zihan Zheng', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/855766', '', ''),
('MONA LISA=has anyone done this?', 'October 22th, 2019', 'Asking for experience in doing mona lisa treatment', '', 'ILC, 2cm, Stage IIA, Grade 2, 0/1 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-', '', '', 'One patient said that mona lisa is expensive, but worth for her. She did not feel as dry overall. Another patient said that it was painless, but a little bit uncomfortable.', 'Zihan Zheng', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/849219', '', ''),
('MONA LISA=has anyone done this?', 'Oct 22th, 2016', 'Gynecoligist recommended Mona Lisa after having done pelvic floor therapy due to post chemo atrophy.', '', 'ILC Stage IIA', '', '', 'Although pricey and unknown if covered by most insurance, it has proved to effective to other patients, helping to reduce dryness and discomfort. However, it is rare so it was unavailable at the initial patient\'s doctor. ', 'Geon Kim', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/849219', '', ''),
('Monitoring for recurrence - what do your doctors suggest?', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/857303', '', ''),
('MRI prep-- anxiety kicking in-any suggestions???', 'october 2017', 'patient is asking for tips to overcome anxiety before MRI exam ', 'Grade 2, 0/1 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'Stage 2A, scan anxiety', '', '', 'Remember that youre not alone. Many patients feel the same anxiety and concern going for an MRI. Scheduling your MRI in advance may give you more time to be emotionally prepared. You can also try doing something you enjoy to help take your mind off of it. In case the anxiety was getting too severe that it interferes with your daily life, you can ask you physical for benzodiazepines such as Xanax to help relieve stress. ', 'Amira Elfergani', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/859767', '', ''),
('Multi-focal and scared', 'September 2018', 'Patient wants to know if multi-focal tumors can decrease their chance of survival ', ' IDC, Right, 2cm, Stage IIB, Grade 2, 2/2 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2', 'Stage IIB', '', '', 'patients who have had tumors that are muticentric have had \"unilateral mastectomy\"\". Patients learned from MO that multifocal and multicentric do not lessen chance of survival \"', 'Amen Aiwekhoe', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/859029', '', ''),
('Multi-focal and scared', 'September 2018', 'Whether multi-focal would change her prognosis', 'IDC, Right, 2cm, Stage IIB, Grade 2, 2/2 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'Stage IIB', '', '', 'Being multi focal does NOT change patients\' prognosis. Multicentric or multifocal tumors do NOT lessen people\'s survival chances.', 'Zihan Zheng', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/859029', '', ''),
('Multifocal Breast Cancer what stage am I', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/812454', '', ''),
('Mum diagnosed doing some research for her', 'September 2018', '', 'IDC,  3.5cm(unidentified location),  Stage 2A, Grade 2/3, ER 8/8,PR-, HER 2-', 'Stage 2A', '', '', 'Patient was put on letrozole in order to decrease lump size but  noticed that their lump continue to increase while taking letrozole. Patients suggest Adriamycin + Cytoxin and later Taxol or Taxotere + Carboplatin for an agressive approach. Due to the patient maternal cousins tumor growth, doctor\'s have implemented surgery and radiation are local treatments; which is commonly used to remove invasive cancer where it has already been detected. ', 'Amen Aiwekhoe', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/866990', '', ''),
('Mum diagnosed doing some research for her', 'September 11, 2018', 'Inquirer\'s mother had surgery for stage 2a grade 2/3 approx 3.5cm idc. However, post-op she is now diagnosed with 2/4 cancerous lymph nodes. Inquirer wants to know any experience available for her mother.', '', '', '', '', 'Inquirer\'s mother had history with diagnosis as being put on letrozole didnt help decrease lump size. However, with chemo due to start, it should prove to curb Grade 3 cells effectively as a systematic treatment, rather than the local treatments the inquirer\'s mother has gone through.', 'Geon Kim', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/866990', '', ''),
('My daughters tribute  Hope I posted this correctly Bravado', 'November 2015 ', '', 'DC, Right, 2cm, Stage IIA, Grade 2, 0/2 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-', '', '', '', 'Patient posted postive video of daughter dancing. I ', 'Amen Aiwekhoe', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/846027', '', ''),
('My daughters tribute  Hope I posted this correctly Bravado', 'July 16th, 2016', '', 'IDC, Right, 2cm, Stage IIA, Grade 2, 0/2 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-', '', '', '', 'The patient posted a video of her daughter dancing on the stage, encouraging cabcer patients to live with positive and optimistc attitude.', 'Zihan Zheng', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/846027', '', ''),
('My mom has Stage 2 Breast Cancer according to Histopath results', 'Feb 18, 2018', 'The person is asking for advice regarding her mom who is going to experience chemo or radiation', 'Her mom\'s up for mastectomy in the next few days and she\'ll be having her left breast removed. She had her biopsy last week and the results show there are cancer cells on her lymph nodes. She was told the next step may be radiation or chemotheraphy', 'Stage 2 bc', '', '', 'After the mastectomy the pathologist will look at the tumor closely. Staging might change because it partly depends on the maximum size of the tumor and sometimes the mammograms/ultrasounds are not as precise. After the surgery, patient will probably have drains - tubes stitched or taped into the skin, to help drain fluid/blood from the incision. She may need to sleep upright for a bit & she will need some help around the house. Pain is usually well managed with medication. Decisions regarding chemotherapy are based on how aggressive the tumor is, its spread, its response to hormonal treatments, and the patient\'s ability to tolerate chemo side effects. Depending on her hormonal receptor status, she may also qualify for something called OncotypeDX where they analyze the tumor and try to predict its risk of recurrence. That can also help with the decision to pursue or skip chemo. Radiation is what is used in the area to kill any cells that might escape surgery. It tends to cause fatigue and skin damage but is by most accounts easier to deal with than chemo. ', 'Zihan Zheng', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/862596', '', ''),
('My mom is refusing to take chemo, I am scared for recurrence', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/831933', '', ''),
('My mother has lost feeling on the side of her breast', 'Dec 2013', 'concerned about losing feeling on the side of the breast after removal of lymph nodes', 'Lymphadenectomy ', 'not given ', '', '', 'Numbness is very common after lymph node removal, and it usually subsides with time. ', 'Amira Elfergani', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/815898', '', ''),
