('Need Advice - Sister Just Diagnosed.', 'August 2014', 'Needs advice while helping a loved one with cancer feel stronger going through chemo ', '', 'stage 2', '', '', 'Educating a newly diagnosed patient on their diagnosis, treatment, prognosis, and possible side effects will help them feel more secure going through this journey. Try to provide love, reassurance, and support even when it looks like they dont need it. Small ways to do this are helping with household chores and/or surprising them with a gift or a phone call.', 'Amira Elfergani ', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/823965', '', ''),
('Need Advice - Sister Just Diagnosed.', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/823965', '', ''),
('Need continued reassurance-- can you help?', 'June 7, 2014', 'The patient is asking for encouraging words because she is probably got thyroid cancer and she felt overwhelmingly scared', '', 'ILC, 2cm, Stage IIA, Grade 2, 0/1 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-', '', '', 'Thyroid cancer is treatable and curable, but a lot of patients spend most of the day trying to convince yourself you are fine, have a hour or two of relief and then bam, back into panic mode. Cycle repeats itself.', 'Zihan Zheng', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/821756', '', ''),
('Need continued reassurance-- can you help?', 'Aug 25, 2014', 'The poster is asking for advice about how she can help her sister who does not ask for help or sypathy', 'Just been diagnosed with Stage 2 and will need 18 weeks of chemo', '', '', '', 'Even though no one would willingly volunteer for treatment like that, patients still manage to get through it. Her clinic should have staff that can educate, reassure and provide support even if she thinks she doesn\'t need any.', 'Zihan Zheng', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/821756', '', ''),
('Need help off the ledge', 'June 10, 2014', 'The patient is extremely anxious about her biopsy because she has not got any message back from the doctor', '', 'ILC, 2cm, Stage IIA, Grade 2, 0/1 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-', '', '', 'Thyroid cancer is very curable. I have also heard that the surgery is not too big a deal either.', 'Zihan Zheng', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/821854', '', ''),
('Need help off the ledge', 'June 2014', 'Patient is worried about biopsy and what to do about the results given.', '', 'Stage IIA', '', '', 'According to the National Cancer Institute, papillary thyroid cancer, which this patient has, can be treated and usually cured. ', 'Katherine Brizuela', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/821854', '', ''),
('Need help on when to tell my children', '', 'The patient is trying to decide when to tell her children about her health status', 'Just diagnosed on Jan.8th and she was scheduled for a lumpectomy on Jan.23th.', 'Right, 2cm, Stage IIA, Grade 2, 0/2 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-', '', '', 'Though it is hard to give the news to your children, it\'s nice to be able to spend time with each child and answer his or her different questions. It makes a big difference in how you present it. If you stay light about it your kids won\'t get too scared.', 'Zihan Zheng', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/869371', '', ''),
('Need help on when to tell my children', 'January 2019 ', 'Patient needs help deciding whether to tell her children about her diagnosis ', 'right lumpectomy, sentinel lymph node removal, radiation, hormonal therapy ', 'Right, 2cm, Stage IIA, Grade 2, 0/2 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-', '', '', 'Its always hard to share your diagnosis with your children; especially, when you dont know that much about it yet. However, it can be very helpful to have your familys support and reassurance. You can tell your children the news in different ways depending on they age. For example, you can inform a young child without going into too many details so they dont get scared. On the other hand, older children are more able to comprehend your diagnosis and treatment options, and will likely offer to help as much as they can.', 'Amira Elfergani ', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/869371', '', ''),
('neoadjuvant results', 'March 28, 2018', 'She is trying to hear some good news stories as she finishes her last two chemo treatments.', 'She had one tumor that shrank a lot and one that seems slightly smaller. Her oncologist says sometimes the cancer cells die but the tumor size doesnt change much. She is Er positive so a lot of shrinkage not expected.', 'DCIS/IDC, Right, 2cm, Stage IIA, Grade 3, 0/7 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-', '', '', 'A responder reported her pain at the tumor site and in the upper part of breast. Also a sense of fullness, like when she get her period.', '', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/863577', '', ''),
('neoadjuvant results', 'March 28, 2018', 'Patient is asking if it is possible for tumor cells to die without the tumor shrinking', 'ER+ and doing last two chemo treatments.', 'Stage 2A Breast Cancer', '', '', 'Sometimes cancer cells can die but the tumor wont get smaller. MRI can show false positives from this even if tumor cells are gone or reduced. Sometimes breasts can feel pain/aches/fullness.', 'Devansh Dwivedy', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/863577', '', ''),
('nervous and feeling alone', 'Jan 8th 2016', 'Patient has had a tumor for a long time which just now turned cancerous, and she worries that it might spread in the future to her lymph nodes, not understanding how it can stay for so long without doing so already.', 'Large tumor present for years.', 'Stage 2A breast cancer', '', '', 'Mostly people giving words of support that the patient isn\'t alone. Another person shared a story of having non cancerous tumors stay inside for years and that many tumors stay benign for years before becoming cancerous.', 'Devansh Dwivedy', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/839697', '', ''),
('nervous and feeling alone', 'January 8, 2016', 'The patient has concersn regarding a longstadning tumor and the probability of it turning cancerous and metastisizing to lymphnodes', 'Longstanding tumor', 'Stage 2A Breast Cancer, Grade 2, 0/2 nodes, ER+/PR+, HER2-', '', 'Nervous, Alone', 'Community support for patient, reassuring patient is not alone. Other patient explained how she had an undedtected tumor that was cancerous, nom-metastisizing, and how she framed her mindset to have a positive outlook and not worrry as much.', 'Harrison Klinski', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/839697', '', ''),
