('questions about check ups after treatment???stressed!', 'Apr 2017 ', 'patient is distressed about having to wait for a long time until her next follow up after treatment ', 'patient had chemotherapy and a  double mastetomy', 'IDC, Left, 3cm, Stage IIA, Grade 3, ER-/PR-, HER2- (FISH)', '', '', 'it is not unusual to have a 5-6 months gap between visits; espicially if you\'re not showing any symptoms that indicate you might need any more tests. Patients doing hormonal therapy usually have more frequent visits.', 'Amira Elfergani ', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/854583', '', ''),
('Questions about chemo', 'Aug 2016 ', 'patient is concerned about undergoing chemotherapy (processs and side effects) ', 'patient had a lumpectomy and a lymph node removal ', 'stage 2BC, 1.6cm', '', '', 'It is completely normal to feel scared and anxious going into chemo; the experience is different for everyone. The treatment usually has side effects (like nausua, fatigue, hot flashes, hair loss), but many medications are available to help control them. Remember to stay hydrated and keep a positive attitude towards your treatment.', 'Amira Elfergani', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/846584', '', ''),
('radiation', 'Nov 2014', 'patient is concerned about the side effects of radiation ', 'patient had a left lumpectomy and a axillary lymph node removal, followed by chemotherapy ', 'DCIS, 1cm, Stage II, Grade 3, ER+, HER2+', '', '', 'In general, radiations seems to have some side effets. Check the following sites for more information: https://www.breastcancer.org/treatment/radiation , https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/70', 'Amira Elfergani', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/826022', '', ''),
('Radiation and survival stats', 'Sept 2013', 'patient is looking for statistics that show the effects of radiation on survival rates ', 'patient has done chemotherapy, radiation, and hormonal therapy. She also had a right lymph node removal and mastectomy ', 'IDC, 2cm, Stage IIIA, Grade 3, ER+/PR+, HER2-', 'Recurrence Queries', '', 'Radiations have a 25% chance of preventing future recurrance. The following sites can help assess the benefits of radiation after a lumpectomy or a mastectomy: http://esciencenews.com/articles/2010/06/02/radiation.after.mastectomy.improves.breast.cancer.survival http://www.nytimes.com/2011/10/20/health/research/20cancer.html?_r=0', 'Amira Elfergani ', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/811342', '', ''),
('Radiation with expanders? What do I do!', 'May 2016 ', 'patient is concerned about undergoing radiation following breast reconstruction with expanders  ', 'patient had a double mastectomy followed by chemotherapy, radiation, and breast reconstruction surgery', 'stage 2B, 5cm, one positive lymph node', 'Right Treatment?', '', 'it is recommended to get the TE filled before starting radiation. This is very impostant because the TE would move yoyr muscle and skun away from the heart and lungs; thus, protecting those ograns from radiation. You might also want to consider waiting for 6 months to a year for your skin to heal after radiation before doing the exchange, and to decrease the chance of a capsular contracture ', 'Amira Elfergani', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/844455', '', ''),
