('Stage2 A/B', 'November 2013 ', 'What is the difference between stage IIA and IIB?', 'New lumpectomy patient, Oncotype score 12, ', 'ILC, 2cm, stage IIA, grade 2, 0/3 nodes, ER+/PR+,HER2-', 'Data interpretation', '', 'Staging is not done until after surgery and the completion of post-operative pathology. This is the breakdown of staging as per as the site: \nStage IIA: \n        - No tumor in breast but cancer (>2mm) is found in 1 to 3 axillary lymph nodes or in lymph nodes near breast bones. \n        - Tumor measures 2 cm or smaller and has spread to axillary lymph nodes\n        - The tumor is between 2cm and 5 cm and has not spread to axillary lymph nodes. \n     \nStage IIB: \n        - Tumor is between 2cm and 5 cm; small groups of breast cancer cells (between 0.2mm and 2mm) are found in lymph nodes.\n        - Tumor is between 2cm and 5 cm; cancer has spread to 1-3 axillary lymph nodes near the breastbone. \n        - Tumor is larger than 5cm but has not spread to the axillary lymph nodes. \n', 'Kriti Bhardwaj ', 'https://community.breastcancer.org/forum/145/topics/814889', '', ''),
